<html>
<body>
<title>Gary Palmer -- Labor Union Politicking</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Labor Union Politicking
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>
While watching the Democratic National Convention, I noticed that a 
disproportionate number of the delegates were wearing or holding 
emblems of the National Education Association (NEA).  
<p>
I can't say that I was surprised.  I had just read a report from the 
Alexis de Tocqueville Institution (AdTI) on the political influence of 
various groups, particularly labor unions.  According to AdTI, labor 
political action committees (PACs) are by far the most partisan of all 
PACs.  Based on the latest Federal Election Commission data for the 
1995-96 campaign cycle, the study found that, while the leading 
business groups have been pro-Republican in their contributions, they 
have still given more than 20 percent of their funds to Democratic 
candidates.  The partisanship ration of business contributions to 
Republicans over Democrats is four-to-one.
<p>
But when it comes to trial lawyers, big labor, and the teacher's 
unions, big business is out of its league.  Trial lawyers contribute 
to Democrats over Republicans by seven-to-one.  In the 1995-96 
election cycle the trial lawyers gave $1,359,475 to Democratic 
candidates but only $188,500 to Republican candidates, hardly enough 
to buy an election for one judge in Alabama.  
<p>
Big labor is even more partisan.  Labor unions contributed barely two 
percent of their funds to Republican candidates, or $1 for every $44 
to Democrats.  The NEA and the American Federation of Teachers (AFT) 
are the most blatantly pro-Democrat with 99 percent of their funds 
going to Democratic candidates.  The NEA gave Democrats $1.2 million 
and only $5,350 to Republicans; the AFT gave the Democrats $446,375 
and only $4,250 to Republicans.
<p>
What is so odd about all of this is that in the last couple of 
elections, with the exception of the trial lawyers, a near majority of 
the labor union members and teachers have voted for Republican 
candidates.  School teachers and union workers are routinely far more 
conservative in their social, cultural, and political views than the 
candidates whose campaigns their dues money supports.  Based on this 
information it is pretty obvious that the leadership of big labor and 
the teachers' unions are forcing a liberal agenda on their members and 
paying for it with the members' own money.
 <p>
Many teachers and union members are not aware that they do not have to 
give political money to the NEA or their union.  According to a 1988 
Supreme Court decision in Beck v. Communications Workers of America 
unions are only allowed to collect dues for the purpose of collective 
bargaining.  Other dues for political purposes can only be taken with 
the employee's permission.
<p>
Under the Beck decision, teachers and union members in states without 
right to work laws can prevent a portion of their paycheck from going 
to fund political candidates who may or may not represent their views.  
In fact, teachers and union members can request that all dues that 
have been deducted from their paychecks for political purposes be 
refunded.  In right to work states such as Alabama , teachers can 
refuse to pay dues at all.  
<p>
As I understand it, all teachers in Alabama who are members of the 
Alabama Education Association (AEA) are also members of the NEA whose 
liberal social and political agenda is far outside that of mainstream 
America.  For instance, the 1996 NEA Resolutions support such things 
as statehood for the District of Columbia, abortion on demand, 
acceptance of homosexuality, comprehensive sex education, early 
childhood education from birth through age eight, nationalized health 
care, gun control, and multicultural education.  On the other hand, 
the NEA opposes standardized testing of students, minimum competency 
exams for teachers, random drug testing for teachers, and English 
being made our official language.  
<p>
If anyone doubts that the NEA's primary focus is their social and 
political agenda, they need only consider the 1991 Supreme Court case 
Lehnert v. Ferris in which the NEA could only prove that ten percent 
of dues money was spent on collective bargaining.  This means that 
Alabama teachers' membership dues are subsidizing the NEA's political 
and social activism with little input from rank and file.  Members may 
not realize that their NEA dues subsidize the NEA's political activity 
even if their dues money does not go directly to candidates.  
Consequently, taking NEA membership dues out of AEA dues may be the 
only way the NEA could get most  Alabama teachers to join.  
<p>
The NEA, AFT, the big labor unions, and the trial lawyers have a right 
to support any one or any policy they want to, but it is wrong to 
intimidate their members into financing politicians and agendas with 
which they do not agree.   
<p>
Maybe it is time for the teachers and the union members to  ask for 
their money back. 
<p>
 -- <a href="mailto:alfamallia@aol.com">Gary Palmer</a>
<p>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
