<html>
<body>
<title>Clifford D. May --  The Top Sitcoms Of Campaign 96</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
 The Top Sitcoms Of Campaign 96
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

<i>by Clifford D. May</i>
<p>
 August 11, 1996
<p>
Among the more interesting issues this campaign season is free airtime. 
Advocates argue that is the TV industry will just let presidential 
contenders have a few unpaid and unmolested minutes on the tube each 
night, the American political process will be mightily improved.
<p>
In the interest of full disclosure, I should note that I host a TCI news 
program that does give candidates free airtime on cable and public 
television channels around the country. In the interest of fuller disclosure, 
I should add that ardent free airtime proponents dont give a hoot. They 
want the free time to be on the big networks smack in the middle of prime 
time when Americans will have to watch - or face the dismal alternative: 
conversing with members of their family.
<p>
It now appears that the networks are going to comply, albeit reluctantly. 
One reason for their reluctance: The project will eat into time that is 
normally devoted to the nets most profitable sitcoms and dramas.
<p>
Heres a compromise. Have the candidates do guest appearances on the 
regular prime-time shows. As a public service, let me suggest a few script 
ideas:
<p>
<b>The Nanny</b>:
<p>
Clinton asks the Nanny to babysit Chelsea (who has come down with 
chicken pox) until the end of the presidential campaign. The president 
takes a keen interest in the new White Housekeeper. Look sweetie, she 
whines, Im no Annette Bening and you, tubby, aint exactly Michael 
Douglas! Soon after, the Nanny finds herself the target of an FBI 
investigation for misfeasance. Is that anything like Miss Flatbush? she 
wonders. In the climactic final moments of the show, Hillary Rodham 
Clinton tells a congressional subcommittee she does not recall any direct 
involvement in the Nannys dismissal. The irrepressible Nanny laughs 
her annoyingly nasal New York laugh.
<p>
<b>Murphy Brown</b>:
<p>
The famous newswoman invites Bob Dole to be interviewed on <i>FYI</i>. 
Come on, Senator, Murphy jabs inquisitorially, surely you dont 
expect us to believe youve become a supply-sider at this late stage in 
your career?
<p>
Dole goes ballistic: Listen, Murphy or Candy or whatever your name is, 
Ive been tested and tested and tested. You beat up on Danny Quayle 
back whenever that was and now you want to beat up on Bob Dole. Well, 
no siree. Ive had it with you and that namby-pamby liberal goo-goo girl 
Katie Whats-Her-Name, too! So stop lying about my record!
<p>
<b>Seinfeld</b>:
<p>
Kramer signs on as Ross Perots campaign manager, Im telling you, 
Jerry, he says, this guy is the greatest thing since frozen yogurt! Hes 
George Washington and Millard Filmore and Gerald Ford all rolled into 
one!
<p>
Yeah, Jerry replies, With a little <i>My Favorite Martian</i> thrown in.
<p>
Enter Perot who tells Jerry: Son, I need a crackerjack speech writer, one 
who can inject some humor, know what I mean? Humanize me, OK? Ill 
give you a million dollars, what do I care? And you can handle my 
foreign policy, too? Know anything about NAFTA?
<p>
Dont they sell auto parts?
<p>
Close enough, says Perot. Youre hired.
<p>
<b>E.R.</b>:
<p>
At a joint appearance with Ross Perot, Dick Lamm is knocked off the 
stage - Whoops! Sorry, says Perot - and has to be rushed to the 
emergency room. If Im a hopeless case, he tells the George Clooney 
character, dont waste expensive resources on me. Consider the next 
generation.
<p>
And here are a few more ideas I dont have sufficient space to flesh out:<br>
<b>Unsolved Mysteries</b>: Ross Perots daughters wedding.<br>
<b>Americas Funnies Home Videos</b>: Ross Perots daughters wedding.<br>
<b>The X-Files</b>: Aliens crash Ross Perots daughters wedding.<br>

</blockquote></blockquote>
<p>
