<html>
<body>
<title>C.H. (Max) Freedman -- The 'Peach Juice Shot': A New Media Low</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
The 'Peach Juice Shot': A New Media Low
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

<i>by C.H. (Max) Freedman</i>
<p>
Longtime readers know there's no more vociferous opponent than I of 
frivolous lawsuits and runaway awards. Were I in charge, most such 
litigants and their lawyers would get zilch if they were lucky, jail 
if they weren't.
<p>
But there's one supposed "nuisance" lawsuit where the defendants, 
David Letterman and company, are just fortunate I won't be on the 
jury. Because I would award the plaintiff, Jane Bronstein, no less 
than $10 million in actual damages -- and enough in punitive damages 
to retire a healthy chunk of the national debt.
<p>
Miss Bronstein, an ordinary spectator at the last U.S. Open tennis 
tournament, was innocently eating a peach when a CBS camera happened 
to pan her way. The fruit apparently was a juicy specimen and some of 
the moisture dribbled down her chin before she could dab it away.
<p>
It was at that luckless instant the CBS camera caught her.
<p>
That humiliating footage was gleefully pounced on by David Letterman's 
producers and shown repeatedly on the Letterman show, presumably as a 
symbol of American uncouthness.
<p>
To raise the derision level still higher, Letterman put Miss 
Bronstein's picture on a huge Times Square billboard and referred to 
her in his "Top Ten" feature as a "seductive temptress."
<p>
Miss Bronstein is middle-aged and overweight. According to her lawyer, 
Harvey J. Rothberg, she suffered polio in childhood, went through two 
spinal fusions and has a thyroid condition. Quite enough troubles for 
one individual without some unfeeling louts turning her into a 
national laughing stock.
<p>
But her overweight condition doubtless made her especially attractive 
to those anything-for-a-laugh vultures. Fat lady with peach juice 
slobbering down her chin, and all that.
<p>
I've never talked with Miss Bronstein but, as the original self-
proclaimed bleeding-heart conservative, I might well be even more 
anguished and outraged than she herself over such heartlessness.
<p>
Indeed, my initial fantasy had me avenging this gross violation of 
human dignity by punching Letterman's face into an unrecognizable 
pulp, then having it photographed and shown on national TV -- with an 
equally derisive theme. Maybe something like "Top Ten Happy Faces."
<p>
If suffering were measurable, we might well discover that what the 
Letterman people put Miss Bronstein through far exceeds the suffering 
we allow to be imposed on drug pushers and child molesters.
<p>
One cringes at the thought of this unfortunate woman having to 
encounter numberless strangers on the street and subway who look at 
her and perhaps snicker. Or, even worse, the constant torment of 
wondering if that staring stranger might be snickering inside.
<p>
And those whose moral antennae aren't particularly attuned to the 
distress she's been put through would do well to consider this: It 
could happen to them, too.
<p>
Every one of us, at some time, comes into an ordinary public-place 
situation where an unseen high-tech camera could snare us in a 
potentially mortifying lapse in propriety: an unbuttoned or unzipped 
article of clothing, a hairpiece or bridgework unexpectedly coming 
loose a nose that suddenly runs before we can grab a tissue, etc., 
etc.
<p>
The reader is asked, then: How would you feel if millions of TV 
watchers were made to point and guffaw over that image of you frozen 
at the precise instant of maximum humiliation?
<p>
A South Carolina caller to the "Barry Farber Show" (where we were 
discussing the case) said he'd seen that juice-dripping shot on 
Letterman. He described Miss Bronstein's image as "gruesome"-looking.
<p>
Certainly, there's a First Amendment right to photograph anyone in 
public -- just the way they appear. If that tennis-tournament camera 
had panned across the crowd and Miss Bronstein and her dripping juice 
happened to be part of the shot, so be it. No one can expect to be 
protected from such routine coverage, however unflattering.
<p>
But there's a galaxy of difference between such legitimate incidental 
coverage and intentionally singling someone out just because they look 
fleetingly ridiculous.
<p>
One needn't be a constitutional scholar to reason that if the right to 
privacy means anything at all, it means the right of ordinary citizens 
to be free of the dread of unseen high-tech cameras forever locking 
them into their most awkward instant with the express intent of 
mocking and degrading them in front of the masses.
<p>
Twenty-three years ago, our Supreme Court in one of its most disputed 
decisions ever, decreed that "the right to privacy" extended to the 
right of women to kill their unborn babies.
<p>
That was indeed a remarkable stretch of language and jurisprudence, 
one that this constitutional strict-constructionist deplores.
<p>
But given that our judicial system has indeed stretched privacy rights 
so very far, it would be the height of injustice to deny people like 
Miss Bronstein redress for a privacy invasion incomparably more 
obvious than any involved in abortion cases.
<p>
Defense counsel, in justifying the cruel, shameful exploitation of 
this woman, will doubtless invoke that ancient catch-all, "The 
public's right to know!"
<p>
And if they are allowed to get away with such judicial and verbal 
flim-flammery, then we as a society are no better than those Letterman 
lowlifes who, quite obviously, rationalize that their own career 
ambitions override all humane considerations.
<p>
<p>
<br>

<center>
