<html>
<body>
<title>Michelle Malkin -- Politicians Are Experts At Playing The Kiddie Card</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Politicians Are Experts At Playing The Kiddie Card
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>by Michelle Malkin
<br>Seattle Times
<br>August 27, 1996
</i>
<p>
Did you happen to catch the GOP's brazen exploitation of children as 
political stage props earlier this month? The indignant twittering of 
liberal pundits on this subject crescendoed when Republican National 
Convention keynote speaker Susan Molinari cuddled her 3-month-old baby 
on prime-time television. Shameless! Crass! Maudlin! Deceptive!
<p>
Ah, my dear liberals, I feel your disdain. I felt it four years ago 
when Al Gore Jr. paraded his family's private grief onstage at the 
Democratic National Convention in New York. Remember? Vice President 
Gore shamelessly spun a personal tragedy into political spectacle 
before a TV audience of millions. In 1989, the script went, Gore's 
then-9-year-old son was struck by a car and recovered only after 
painful therapy.
<p>
Young Al Gore III's eyes, recounted his father, "were open with the 
empty stare of death, and we prayed, the two of us, there in the 
gutter, with only my voice." A sniffle here, a sigh there, a 
choreographed nod to little Al for the cameras - and then back to the 
words on the TelePrompter. "Our democracy is lying there in the 
gutter," Daddy Gore analogized, "waiting for us to give it a second 
breath of life."
<p>
Gag me with a pacifier.
<p>
Two years ago this month, I felt that feeling again as I watched a 
fragile little girl named Jennifer Bush pleading for the Clinton 
health-care reform plan on Capitol Hill. Jennifer allegedly suffered 
from chronic digestive problems. Her medical bills totaled more than $ 
2 million and exhausted the family's health-insurance benefits; only 
Clintoncare could save them. Soon, the sick youngster was posing with 
first lady Hillary Clinton, lobbying with the Children's Defense Fund, 
and smiling for promotional posters touting Clintoncare.
<p>
It was a moving letter from Jennifer's devoted mother that caught the 
White House's attention. "Do you know what it is like to choose 
between purchasing groceries for the week to feed your family or 
buying needed medications for your chronically ill child?" Kathleen 
Bush wrote.
<p>
Well, apparently, Mrs. Bush didn't. Florida officials arrested the 
caring mom this spring and charged her with aggravated child abuse and 
fraud in connection with obtaining more than $ 50,000 in medical care 
or charitable donations.
<p>
Independent pediatric specialists conducted extensive tests on 
Jennifer and found no evidence of digestive disorders. Prosecutors 
charged Mommy with deliberately making her child sick to gain 
attention. They also discovered that while the Bush family publicly 
appealed for donations and government aid to pay for Jennifer's 
hospital debts, they were racking up huge credit card bills - for 
trips to the Bahamas and Disney World, kitchen and pool remodeling, 
and a new Harley-Davidson motorcycle.
<p>
Politicians have been kissing babies since time immemorial, but the 
crass infantilization of public policy is new, sickening and scary. 
There is now an almost insurmountable temptation to advocate policy 
initiatives that restrict adult liberties by playing the kiddie card. 
And why not? Whether they advocate a crackdown on television violence, 
censoring of the Internet, health-care reform, or expansion of 
government's role in any other area, activists can effectively 
neutralize serious debate by claiming to speak for The Children.
<p>
Perhaps the mother of all kiddie ploys came last week, when President 
Clinton announced sweeping Food and Drug Administration regulations of 
tobacco for the sake of - who else? - The Children. A multiculturally 
correct brood of youngsters, who each donned a Crayola red T-shirt 
proclaiming the wearer to be a TOBACCO-FREE KID, formed a necklace 
around the First Father in the Rose Garden.  Federal public health 
officials insist that the new rules, which give the FDA unprecedented 
authority to regulate cigarettes and smokeless tobacco (but not cigars 
or pipe tobacco) as drug-delivery devices, won't infringe on adult 
civil liberties. But grown-ups who aren't drooling mindlessly over 
this massive regulatory scheme know better.
<p>
If the feds can argue that cigarettes are regulable drug-delivery 
devices, why not caffeinated beverages? Like tobacco products, soda 
pop contain an addictive ingredient marketed aggressively to young 
children for its pharmacological effects ("Do the Dew," "Just for the 
taste of it - Diet Coke," "Mug Root Beer - the foam goes straight to 
your brain").  Or how about chocolate, which neuroscientists in San 
Diego have discovered contains marijuana-like qualities?
<p>
And why not crack down on fatty-snack advertising, too? According to 
Yale diet specialist Kelly Brownell, the average child sees 10,000 
food commercials per year using sports heroes and cartoon characters 
to peddle addictive - and life-threatening - soft drinks, candy and 
sugar-coated cereals.  Anti-smoking activists answer that the teen 
smoking epidemic is uniquely devastating. It is a problem, no 
question, but not an epidemic.
<p>
The most oft-cited data on youth smoking, from the University of 
Michigan's Monitoring the Future project, do show a small increase in 
pre-teen smoking over the past four years. But overall daily smoking 
among 12th-graders has been steadily declining over the past two 
decades. Heavy smoking (a half-pack a day or more) by these high-
school seniors plunged from 17.9 percent in 1975 to 11.2 percent in 
1984, remaining flat for the past decade.
<p>
But never mind all that. There are butts to kick, kids to save, and 
elections to win. The infantilization of America presses forward. 
Shameless, isn't it?
<p>
 -- <a href="mailto:malkin1@ix.netcom.com">Michelle Malkin</a>
<p>
<br>
<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
