<HEAD><title>CRC Personnel</title></HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center><img src="/crc/images/hdr-pers.gif" alt="CRC Personnel"></center>
<P>
<dl>
<a name="Scanlon"></a>
<dt><b>Terrence Scanlon, President</B>
<dd>Scanlon was elected Capital Research Center President in June
1994.  Before joining CRC, he served as vice president for corporate
relations at <a href="http://www.heritage.org">The Heritage Foundation</a>.  His public service career
includes seven years at the Consumer Product Safety Commission,
 including a stint as Chairman during President Ronald Reagan's first term.  He holds a B.A.
in economics from Villanova University.
<P>
<a name="Huberty"></a>
<dt><B>Robert Huberty, Director of Research</B>
<dd>Huberty oversees <a href="/crc/about/pubs.html">CRC publications</a>.  He is former Director of
Academic Programs and the Resource Bank at <a href="http://www.heritage.org">The Heritage Foundation</a>
(1980-93), and earlier was a research assistant to Richard Nixon.
 He received B.A. and M.A. degrees in History from the University
of California, Irvine.
<P>
<a name="Ross"></a>
<dt><B>Gary H. Ross, Director of Development</B>
<dd>Ross joined the CRC staff in May 1996.  He was formerly the development associate at the Leadership Institute.  He earned a masters in political science from American University and a bachelors from the Ohio State University.
<P>
<a name="DeWees"></a>
<dt><B>Natasha D. Clerihue, Director of Communications, Congressional Liaison</B>
<dd>DeWees joined the CRC staff to create the think-tank's first
in-house public relations department.  She has earned two degrees
in journalism:  a bachelor's from Auburn University in Alabama
and a master's from the Medill School of Journalism, Northwestern
University.
<P>
<a name="Jarvik"></a>
<dt><B>Laurence Jarvik, Ph.D,  Cultural Studies Fellow and Editor of <a href="/crc/fw/"><I>Foundation
Watch</I></a> and <a href="/crc/cw/"><i>Culture Watch</i></a></B>
<dd>Jarvik earned his doctorate and master of fine arts in film and
television from UCLA, where he was Hugh Downs Fellow and winner
of the Distinguished Scholar Award.  He attended Swarthmore College
and graduated from the University of California, Berkeley, with
an undergraduate degree in philosophy at age 20. He is editor
of three books concerning the federal government's role in the
arts.
<P>
<a name="Fulk"></a>
<dt><B>Austin Fulk, Research Associate</B>
<dd>Fulk is co-author of <I><a href="/crc/patterns/">Patterns of Corporate Philanthropyi</a>
IX</I>.  Fulk earned a B.A. in Political Science from John Hopkins
University.
<P>
<a name="Oliver"></a>
<dt><B>Daniel T. Oliver, Research Associate and Editor, <a href="/crc/ap/"><I>Alternatives
in Philanthropy</I></B></a>
<dd>Oliver is author of <I>Animal Rights: The Inhumane Crusade</I>.
 He received a B.A. in sociology, <I>cum laude</I>, from the University
of Akron.
<P>
<a name="Pambianco"></a>
<dt><B>Robert Pambianco, Research Associate and Editor, <a href="/crc/trends/"><I>Organization
Trends</I></B></a>
<dd>An expert in issue-oriented advocacy nonprofits, Pambianco's
work has appeared in the <I>Wall Street Journal, <a href="/wash_times/">Washington Times</a></I>,
and <I>Human Events.</I>  A graduate of LaSalle University, Pambianco
is studying law at the Catholic University of America.  He has
been with Capital since 1990.
<P>
<a name="Lacey"></a>
<dt><B>Jill K. Lacey, Research Associate and Editor, <a href="/crc/pcs/"><I>Philanthropy,
Culture &amp; Society</I></B></a>
<dd>Lacey's work on charitable organizations and community service
has appeared in numerous publications including <I>The Detroit
News, San Diego Union Tribune </I>and <I>Chronicle of Philanthropy.</I>
 She is a graduate of St. Peters College in New Jersey and has
been with Capital since 1992.
<P>
<a name="Overbeck"></a>
<dt><B>Lorraine K. Overbeck, Manager, Administration</B>
<dd>Overbeck has been with Capital for more than three years.  She
graduated with honors from Christendom College in 1991.
<P>
<a name="Wood"></a>
<dt><B>David Wood, Development Assistant</B>
<dd>Wood is assistant to the Director of Development.  He received
a B.A. in Political Science from the University of Wisconsin-River
Falls.
<P>
<a name="Wheeler"></a>
<dt><B>Tara Wheeler, Staff Assistant</B>
<dd>Capital's receptionist, Wheeler received her B.A. from the University
of Maryland where she majored in Government and Politics.
<P>
<a name="Olasky"></a>
<dt><B>Marvin Olasky, Senior Fellow</B>
<dd>Olasky is a journalism professor at The University of Texas and
author of <I>The Tragedy of American Compassion</I>.  His latest
work for CRC is as editor of a compilation of <a href="/crc/pcs/"><I>PCS</I></a> essays,
<a href="/crc/books/neighbor.html"><I>Loving Your Neighbor:  A Principled Guide to Personal Charity</I></a>.
<P>
<a name="DiLorenzo"></a>
<dt><B>Thomas J. DiLorenzo, Senior Fellow</B>
<dd>DiLorenzo is an economist at the Sellinger School of Business
and Management at Loyola College in Baltimore.  His latest book 
 is <a href="/crc/books/elderly.html"><I>Frightening America's Elderly:</a> How the Age Lobby Holds Seniors Captive.
</I>
<P>
<a name="Holt"></a>
<dt><B>Tom Holt, Visiting Fellow</B>
<dd>Holt is a former member of the <I>Richmond</I> (Virginia) <I>Times-Dispatch</I>
editorial board and has served as chief of speechwriting and research
to two U.S. secretaries of transportation.  His latest work for
CRC is <a href="/crc/books/nanny.html"><I>The Rise of the Nanny State:  How Consumer Advocates
Try to Run Our Lives</I></a>.  
<P>
<a name="Johnson"></a>
<dt><B>M. Bruce Johnson, Senior Fellow</B>
<dd>Johnson is an economist at the University of California at Santa
Barbara.  His latest work for CRC is the summary essay for <I>Patterns
in Corporate Philanthropy VII</I>.
<P>
<a name="Wooster"></a>
<dt><B>Martin Morse Wooster, Visiting Fellow</B>
<dd>Wooster is an associate editor of <I>The American Enterprise</I>,
a contributing editor and columnist for <I>Reason</I> and a columnist
for the <a href="/wash_times"><I>Washington Times</I></a>.  His latest work for CRC is <a href="/crc/books/pdi.html"><I>The
Great Philanthropists and the Problem of &quot;Donor Intent&quot;</I></a>.
</dl>
