<DOCNO>WT19-B15-160</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000249-B019-51</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/crc/patterns/pcpsumm.html 204.71.237.74 19970108094907 text/html 26111
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 09:49:24 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 18-Mar-96 14:00:49 GMT
Content-length: 25924
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!doctype html public "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Patterns in Corporate Philanthropy VIII -- CRC</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif"><a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<ul>
<center>
<a href="pcptoc.html"><img src="/crc/images/hdr-pcp.gif" border="0" alt="Patterns of Corporate Philantrhopy"></a><br>
</center>
<img src="/crc/images/pcpsumm.gif">
<br>
<br>
<small>
Contents:<br>
<ul><a href="#intro">Introduction</a>
<BR><a href="#how">How Corporate Philanthropy Hurts Traditional Charity</a>
<BR><a href="#whose">Whose Money Is It?</a>
<br><a href="#corporate">Corporate Culpulbility</a>
<BR><a href="#feeding">Feeding the Mouths That Bite Them</a>
<BR><a href="#big">Big Business and Interest Group Liberalism</a>
<BR><a href="#conclusions">Conclusions</a>
<BR><a href="#call">A Call to Action</a>
<P>
<a href="notemeth.html">Methodology and Notes</a>
</ul>
</small>
<a name="intro"></a>
<P>
<br>
When voters rejected George Bush in 1992, liberal commentators and the press argued that the Administration's economic policies were only partly to blame.  They claimed that conservatives cost Bush the presidency by debating social issues and family values.  Partisan liberals went further, concluding that the public had repudiated an entire decade of greed.  All believed that Bill Clinton successfully campaigned as an agent of change.
<P>
	Since the election, Clinton has abandoned most of his &quot;New Democrat&quot; rhetoric and has promoted traditionally liberal policies.  The public feels increasingly uneasy about the nation's direction and the durability of the social fabric.  Why has the President failed to inspire?  The answer is simple.  Americans see all about them the continuing moral and cultural distintegration that accompanies expanding social welfare programs.  They want changes more profound than government programs; they want an end to the something-for-nothing mentality that passes for public participation in the modern welfare state.
<P>
	During the past thirty years nonprofit public affairs and advocacy groups have claimed to speak for the American public.  Concentrated in the nation's capital and proliferating as the federal government identifies ever more problems as its responsibility, these groups have become the idea factories and advertising agencies of public policy debate.  At key points in what Washington euphemistically calls &quot;the policy process&quot; advocacy groups become very influential.  By providing information and useful arguments to policymakers, the media and the public, they affect political outcomes.  When they advocate policies in &quot;the public interest,&quot; public affairs groups influence whether government will afford its citizens opportunities or whether it will distribute entitlements.  In the case of Randall Robinson's TransAfrica, an advocacy group can even affect whether America chooses to go to war.  Corporate contributions to nonprofit advocacy organizations implicitly acknowledge their importance.  But corporations have failed to understand how they operate or what they really want.  
<P>
	For eight years Capital Research Center has tracked corporate giving to nonprofit public affairs groups.  Regrettably, Corporate America continues to fund groups that advocate welfare state policies.  Corporate philanthropy too often supports interest groups that denigrate market incentives and economic growth.  Whatever their motivation, corporate managements are contributing stockowner funds to groups that obstruct genuine economic, social and political reforms that can renew America's traditions of limited government, a free market, and respect for individual rights and responsibilities.
<P>
	Public debate over the health care &quot;crisis&quot; offers a telling example of how advocacy groups use corporate dollars.  For decades advocacy groups and think tanks championed health care policy ideas that can be found in the plan devised by Hillary Clinton's health care task force.  The Administration's plan for &quot;universal coverage&quot; through regional health care &quot;alliances&quot; and its rhetorical emphasis on &quot;managed competition&quot; can be traced to a variety of nongovernmental sources: from the Progressive Policy Institute, a project of the the Democratic Leadership Council (which Gov. Bill Clinton once chaired) to the Children's Defense Fund (which Hillary Clinton once chaired).  Planned Parenthood joined the coalition for universal coverage on condition that it include taxpayer-funded abortions on demand.  As the entries in this study indicate, these advocacy organizations received financial support from major American corporations.  How many of the companies funding them would eventually spend far more to fight the Administration's 1342 page health insurance bill? 
<P>
	Nonprofit advocacy groups cannot market their ideas without money.  They depend on tax-deductible contributions from individual donors sympathetic to their aims, grant-giving foundations, and corporations.  But the financial contribution of a large corporation, even a modest donation, has one added benefit.  Corporate money can obscure the radical economic or political agenda of an advocacy group, giving it an unearned credibility with otherwise cautious individual donors.  Indeed, corporate funding can help a nonprofit increase its budget exponentially, opening doors to other corporate and foundation donors and to government grants.
<P>
	It is clear that too many corporate executives just don't get it.  The trends in corporate philanthropy have not improved during the eight years Capital Research Center has conducted this study.  There are few individual exceptions.  Among the 43 most significant corporate contributors to nonprofit advocacy groups (<a href="/crc/patterns/pcp10b.html">SEE TEN BEST GIVERS</a>), only Eli Lilly received a grade of &quot;A&quot;, the first corporation to be so designated in eight years.  No corporations received a &quot;B.&quot;  Nine corporations received a &quot;C&quot; grade; of these, however, only Amoco and Cigna displayed slight right-of-center giving patterns.  The patterns of public affairs giving by Coca-Cola, Anheuser-Busch, Fannie Mae, and J.P. Morgan earned these corporations the lowest possible grade -- &quot;F&quot;.  All others on the list earned &quot;D&quot; grades.  Waste Management, General Mills, Dayton Hudson, and American Express--each with a long-standing tradition of funding Left-oriented advocacy groups--are especially familiar faces on this list.
<P><br>
<a name="how"></a>
<B>How Corporate Philanthropy Hurts Traditional Charity</B>
<P>	
Traditional charity involves individual acts of virtue:  charitable individuals voluntarily offer direct assistance to the needy.  Traditional charities--groups like the Boy Scouts, Catholic Charities, the Red Cross, and the Salvation Army--work to alleviate suffering and assist the recovery of personal independence.  In contrast, the welfare state mandates social programs that empower service professionals, generate dependency in their clients, and promote a sense of entitlement in both.  Proponents of so-called &quot;progressive philanthropy&quot; are encouraging corporations and foundations to adopt a new philosophy of philanthropic giving.  Occupying leadership positions in key organizations like the Council on Foundations, they deemphasize support for traditional charities and would shift philanthropy's financial resources to nonprofit advocacy groups, especially those that actively promote welfare state programs.
<P>
	The majority of companies surveyed in this study devote less than 10 percent of their charitable contributions to nonprofit advocacy groups.  But the trend toward advocacy and away from traditional charity is growing.  Moreover, most of the corporations that contribute significantly to nonprofit advocacy groups (<a href="/crc/patterns/pcp10w.html">SEE TEN WORST MISGIVERS</a>) favor groups that are committed to expanding the welfare state.  
<P>
<ul>
<li>Exxon contributed the most money to nonprofit advocacy groups--more than $2.7 million.  Other members of the million dollar club included Aetna, Ford, NYNEX, AT&amp;T and General Electric.  Together these five companies gave nearly $6.4 million to largely center-left and liberal interest groups.
<li>IBM devoted more than 25 percent of its philanthropic dollars to advocacy groups in a year when it lost almost $7 billion.  Monsanto gave over 24 percent of its total contributions to nonprofit advocacy groups; Archer Daniels Midland gave over 17 percent.
<li>Fannie Mae contributed almost 30 percent of its philanthropy--almost $2 million--to left-of-center advocacy groups.  None of the company's 26 grants to advocacy nonprofits went to a right-of-center group.  Freddie Mac gave over 13 percent to advocacy groups.  Both corporations enjoy government guarantees enabling them to make huge profits in an otherwise risky secondary mortgage market.
<li>FMC, Unocal, Reynolds Metals, W.R. Grace, and Amoco deserve recognition for supporting advocacy groups that favor competitive free markets and limited government.  Sun Microsystems is the only company whose charitable contributions program does not fund nonprofit advocacy groups.
</ul>
<P>
	The advocacy groups that bid for corporate philanthropy enjoy the same tax-exemption as a church or a traditional charity, even though they recognize no obligation to provide charity's direct assistance.  When corporations fund these nonprofits from their philanthropic budgets, they give traditional charities an incentive to alter their priorities to compete for the advocacy dollar.  Worse, the advocacy groups that receive corporate funding tend to be those most favorable to welfare state policies, policies that co-opt the aims and undermine the achievements of genuine charity. 
<P><br>
<a name="whose"></a>
<B>Whose Money Is It?</B>
<P>
	Conservatives understand that limited government is necessary for civil order as well as for liberty, and that local government works best to provide services protecting the community.  Conservatives understand that religion and education instill good character in the young and that a strong family is the best safety net.  Conservatives know that work creates wealth, and that property rights protect opportunity.  Does it matter whether big business agrees?  Shouldn't corporations be free to make charitable contributions to whichever groups they favor?
<P>
	The answer is no.  Charity is a voluntary and virtuous act of giving by one person to another.  But the companies examined in this study issue shares of stock that are publicly traded.  Except insofar as they are shareholders, company executives are <I>management</I>, not <I>owners</I>.  To truly engage in an act of charity with corporate funds, management would need to inform shareholders of the company's proposed contribution and obtain their consent. Management's fiduciary trust requires that its decisions properly represent shareholder interests.
<P>
	Milton Friedman has argued that &quot;socially responsible&quot; companies are those that operate most profitably for their owners.  In doing that they supply jobs, products, and services that are in demand.   When USAir indefinitely suspended its corporate philanthropic program until the company returned to profitability, it was taking Friedman's advice.  Sadly, other companies ignored the message in their bottom line.  In 1991, the most recent year for which information in this study can be gathered, 21 corporations gave away their shareholders' money despite the red ink on their books:
<P>
<ul>
<li>Equitable contributed $3.5 million to charity, or nearly 11 percent of the $32.2 million the company lost.  Ashland Oil's philanthropy budget amounted to $5.2 million, or close to 8 percent of its $66.8 million loss.
<li>IBM lost nearly $6.9 billion, but still found nearly $3 million to give away.  General Motors lost $2.6 billion, but found $21 million for charity.
<li>Ford Motor gave away over $19 million even as it lost more than $500 million.  The St. Paul Companies made contributions of $8.8 million while losing over $232 million.  Westinghouse gave $6.8 million to charity in a year in which it lost $953 million.
</ul>
<P>
	At least the corporate managements at Georgia-Pacific, W.R. Grace, and Reynolds Metals could claim they were pursuing their companies' longer term interests by contributing to right-of-center think tanks and advocacy groups.  But what excuse could the managements at 18 other money-losing companies give for dispensing shareholder monies?  It was, after all, not theirs.  Corporate philanthropists may fancy themselves modern-day Robin Hoods.  But management's fiduciary trust is not a license to steal. 
<P><br>
<a name="feeding"></a>
<B>Feeding the Mouths That Bite Them</B>
<P>
	The old argument that what's good for business is good for America (and vice-versa) is enjoying a peculiar revival.  Advocacy groups claim that what's bad for particular American businesses is bad for America.  When a dynamic, competitive market threatens the well-being of major American corporations shouldn't something be done?  For instance, Ford and Chrysler each gave $150,000 to the protectionist Economic Strategy Institute.  General Motors gave $17,000.  Won't contributions to this group fund the studies that protect jobs and return profits to Detroit?
<P>
	Such claims ignore the interest of shareholders in the <I>long-term</I> competitiveness of their company.  Anti-market policies may help companies retain current market share and protect top management in the <I>short-term</I>.  But the benefits of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and the Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs (GATT) outweigh any negative consequences from foreign competition.
<P>
	The automobile industry offers a particularly salient example: Artificial price barriers like tariffs or &quot;voluntary&quot; limits on imports have not stopped foreign companies from setting up shop in the United States.  Consumer demand for a superior product has pressured Detroit automakers to improve auto quality or lose market share.
<P>
	If management gives away shareholder profits through a corporate philanthropy program, wouldn't it be best to contribute to traditional charities that provide direct services?  If management looks for advocacy groups to fund, why not those that encourage self-help and individual responsibility like Robert Woodson's National Center for Neighborhood Enterprise?  There is no ethical explanation or excuse for supporting proponents of the welfare state.  Consider the following examples of self-defeating corporate philanthropy:
<P><ul>

<li>ACORN, the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now, received $123,000 from financial institutions BankAmerica, Fannie Mae, First Chicago and J.P. Morgan.  ACORN activists are best known for targeting banks, telling them who should receive minority set-aside loans.  Banks that reject ACORN's advice risk charges that they have failed to comply with the Community Reinvestment Act.
<li>The Center for Community Change, which supports raising personal and corporate taxes, received 
$319,000 in corporate contributions.  Fannie Mae contributed $100,000; Aetna - $70,000; Dayton Hudson - $34,500; and AT&amp;T - $25,000.
<li>Children's Defense Fund wants to nationalize distribution of child vaccines and greatly expand Medicaid and Head Start.  Once chaired by Hillary Clinton and then by Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala, CDF backed the Clinton health plan and prods the Administration's social welfare agenda.  Corporations gave CDF over $700,000 in 1992.  This includes $75,000 from J.P. Morgan, $70,000 from American Express, $60,000 from Fannie Mae, and $50,000 each from Aetna, AT&amp;T, Citicorp, and Coca-Cola.  Merrill Lynch provided at least $36,000, General Mills gave $35,600, and Dayton Hudson gave $30,000 to CDF.
<li>The Alliance to Save Energy has supported a fifty-cent per gallon gasoline tax that would dampen consumer demand for larger and safer, but less fuel-efficient American-made cars.  Ashland Oil, Chevron, Chrysler and Texaco each contributed $5,000 to the Alliance.
<li>Exxon contributed $5,000 to the Environmental Law Institute, which economist Paul Craig Roberts credits with formulating the legal rationale for Exxon's criminal indictment for the <I>Valdez</I> oil spill. 
<li>The Audubon Society and the National Wilderness Federation oppose exploration in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge.  Chevron and Enron combined to give Audubon $30,000, while Amoco gave $46,000 to the National Wildlife Federation.  NWF also supports an &quot;Environmental Quality Amendment&quot; to the Constitution and would elevate the Environmental Protection Agency to cabinet-level status.  Chevron also gave $5,000 to the Center for Marine Conservation, which has blocked oil drilling in Monterey Bay.
</ul><P>
	Why do corporations feed the mouths that bite them?  The answer is unclear because many corporations are unwilling to reveal which charities they fund.  In responding to Capital Research Center queries, many corporate contributions managers claimed that company policy prohibited them from disclosing grant recipients lists.  Others insisted that the requested information was confidential or &quot;proprietary.&quot;  In a &quot;politically correct&quot; environment, companies are torn between their desire for good public relations and their fear of public controversy. 
<P><br>
<a name="corporate"></a>
<B>Corporate Culpability</B>
<P>
	Evidence of corporate support for nonprofit proponents of the welfare state is compelling.  Of 36 nonprofit advocacy groups that received more than $250,000 in corporate contributions, 27 had liberal public policy agendas.  It is striking that the top five left-of-center groups received over $9 million in corporate contributions, over $1 million more than the total corporate contributions to 87 right-of-center groups.  The top five:
<P>
<ul>
<li>The Urban League received over $3 million from corporations.  It supports an &quot;Urban Marshall Plan for America,&quot; a $500 billion expansion of the welfare state to achieve the &quot;goal of black-white parity by the year 2000.&quot;  Toward this end it opposed U.S. military action against Iraq fearing the deaths of a disproportionate number of blacks.  The League receives over half of its $26.5 million budget from the federal government. 
<li>The Enterprise Foundation received nearly $2 million.  A recipient of large U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development contracts, it would dramatically increase federal funding for low-income housing.
<li>The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has seen its proud history of civil rights activism tarnished by scandal.  And its support of racial quotas in hiring undermines a commitment to equal rights.  The NAACP received nearly $1.6 million in corporate contributions.
<li>The Nature Conservancy boasts that it is &quot;the largest private system of nature sanctuaries in the world.&quot;  But it has sold millions of acres of private lands to the federal government at a profit to itself, actions for which it was reprimanded by the General Accounting Office.  Corporations contributed $1.2 million to the Conservancy.
<li>The Committee for Economic Development supported the government mandates of the Family and Medical Leave Act.  CED Chairman Owen Butler opposes school choice initiatives.  The Committee received nearly $1.2 million from corporations.  
</ul>
<P><br>
<a name="big"></a>
<B>Big Business and Interest Group Liberalism</B>
<P>
This edition of <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy</I> tracks the source and destination of nearly $37 million in corporate philanthropy.  This is the amount that 129 of the nation's largest companies contributed to over 300 nonprofit advocacy groups in 1992, the most recent year for which records are available.  For eight years Capital Research Center has surveyed giving to nonprofit advocacy groups by America's largest corporations as determined by <I>Forbes Magazine</I>.  Our findings have never been worse:  Big businesses gave $3.46 to left-leaning interest groups for every dollar contributed to right-of-center groups.  
<P>
	Recipient groups are classified according the the following criteria:
<P><ul>
<li><I>The Change-Oriented Right</I> includes conservative organizations like The Heritage Foundation, Hoover Institution and Capital Research Center, as well as market liberal and libertarian groups like the Cato Institute, Reason Foundation and Competitive Enterprise Institute.  These groups are strong defenders of individual liberty and responsibility, and they are convinced that major cuts in government programs, taxes, and regulations are essential for economic prosperity and personal freedom.  They received only 11% of 1992 corporate contributions to nonprofit pubic affairs groups.
<li><I>The Establishment Right</I> includes the American Enterprise Institute, Center for Strategic and International Studies, and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.  These organizations favor less systemic reforms to eliminate waste and fraud in government and to improve economic efficiency.  These groups actually received slightly less funding from corporations than the Change-Oriented Right.
<li><I>Non-ideological</I> groups like the Center for Governmental Research and the Rand Corporation avoid controversy over political values and offer pragmatic or &quot;good government&quot; policy prescriptions.   They received the smallest share of corporate philanthropy, less than four percent.
<li><I>The Establishment Left</I> consists of moderate center-left groups like the Brookings Institution and the National Alliance of Business, as well as liberal groups like the Urban League, Enterprise Foundation, and Nature Conservancy.  These groups defend government's role as a problem-solver and look favorably on increased government regulation and taxation.  The lion's share of corporate contributions--nearly 64 percent--went to them.
<li><I>The Change-Oriented Left</I> includes groups that favor a government-initiated restructuring of American economic and social institutions.  Groups like the Center for Community Change, Children's Defense Fund, the NAACP, and more radical activists like Greenpeace pursue collectivist public policies through activist politics.  These groups received 11% of corporate contributions.
</ul><P>
	Corporate America's connection to interest group liberalism is most evident when funding of &quot;change-oriented&quot; groups, Left and Right, is compared to corporate funding of &quot;establishment&quot; groups.  Corporate contributions to nonprofit groups on the change-oriented Right were equal to corporate contributions to nonprofit groups on the change-oriented Left.  This finding suggests that corporate funds may neutralize or cancel out the impact of the most determined agents of change.  But the Establishment Left received more than six dollars in corporate contributions for every dollar that went to Establishment Right groups.  Money means influence inside the Washington, D.C. Beltway.  By a six to one margin, corporate executives gave it to liberal interest groups.  Is it any wonder that politics is in gridlock and public policies reinforcing a failed welfare state remain in place?
<P>
<br>
<a name="conclusions"></a>
<B>Conclusions</B>
<P>
<ul>
<li>That big business funds the liberal agenda flies in the face of conventional wisdom.  But the common presumption that American corporations are conservative advocates of the free enterprise system is far from the truth.  The charitable contributions of America's largest companies provide financial support for group interests well to the left of mainstream Americans.
<li>Corporations undermine traditional charities by giving to advocacy groups.  The poor are ill-served when funds that might have been used for them go instead to groups favoring programs of advocacy.
<li>Finally, it is improper for unprofitable corporations to make philanthropic donations.  Worse, it is inexcusable that corporations, profitable or not, contribute to groups whose political agenda undermines the conditions that make possible their own economic prosperity.  In neglecting shareholders' interests in long-term profitability, managers betray their fiduciary trust.
</ul>
<P><br>
<a name="call"></a>
<B>A Call To Action</b>
<P>
What will change the behaviour of corporate management?  If shareholders believe corporate philanthropy is directly or indirectly hurting profits, they may want to confront company policies directly.  Capital Research Center urges corporate shareholders as well as taxpayers, consumers, and citizens to express their dissatisfaction to company executives.  Let them know that corporate contributions:
<P><ul>
	<li>should not take precedence over returns to investors;
	  <li>should not fund advocacy groups over traditional charities;
 	  <li>should not favor liberal interest groups over groups favoring market reform.  
</ul><P>
	Without popular pressure the pattern of bias in corporate philanthropy will continue, and Americans' desire for change will remain frustrated.  If big business will stop funding liberal advocacy groups it may be possible yet to replace the welfare state with the land of opportunity.
<P><br>
<small>
<a href="10b10w.html">Index of Ten Best and Ten Worst Big Corporate Givers</a>



</body>
</html>
