<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><IMG ALT="Foundation Watch" src="/crc/images/hdr-fw.gif"></center>
<font size=+1><i>Foundation Watch Vol. I No. 8</i></font><P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>September 1996</B></FONT><p>
<center><font  size=-1><a href="#pay">Making Americans Pay</a> | <a href="#genius">Global Geniuses</a> | <a href="#letters">Letters to the Editor</a></font></center><p>
<hr>
<a name="pay">
<center><h2>MAKING AMERICANS PAY: THE MACARTHUR FOUNDATION'S PLAN FOR A GLOBAL IRS</h2>
<h3>by Cliff Kincaid</h3></center>
One of America's largest foundations, the $3 billion John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation, has moved ever leftward in recent years.  From the increasingly bizarre choices of recipients for its celebrated "genius" awards to the funding of Parliamentarians for Global Action, MacArthur Foundation grants have come to exemplify "progressive philanthropy" at its most cutting-edge.
Many MacArthur programs fund predictable if radical attempts to shape policy and opinion on public issues.  MacArthur, for instance, funds the far-left Institute for Policy Studies ($650,000 in 1993) for the purpose of developing "A New U.S. Foreign Policy for the 21st Century." Other programs, however, have staked out new ground.  One new endeavor is the field of "international governance" to which the foundation committed $1,589,902 in 1994.  It is the focus of the Foundation's Peace and International Cooperation Program.<p>
At first glance "international governance" might appear to imply support for the programs of the United Nations and its affiliated institutions.  But a closer look suggests something more.  A review of MacArthur Foundation annual reports and MacArthur-funded organizations discloses findings that are certain not to please American taxpayers.<p>
 To finance an expansion of the U.N.'s military, environmental and population control programs the MacArthur Foundation is leading a chorus of voices that over the last several years has been advocating the imposition of international taxes on the United States and other countries.  "International governance" has become a euphemism for encouraging nonprofits, governments and international bodies to undertake projects, task forces, conferences, seminars, monographs, reports and other activities that will help build a constituency for world government that will be supported by ordinary American citizens through payments to an international version of the I.R.S.<p>
MacArthur is careful not to use the term "world government" to describe this ambitious agenda.  But the projects underwritten by the foundation, in particular the private Commission on Global Governance, are partly designed to give the U.N. an independent taxing authority.  If successful, the cash-strapped world body would have the wherewithal to become a full-fledged government and it would become independent of U.S. influence.<p>
Of course, this is a sensitive topic that is subject to countless qualifications and preconditions.  Warnings of "world government" are easily dismissed as fever swamp fantasies.  But those who follow foundation grantmakers notice that they increasingly seek to fund "global solutions" to problems that do not suffer interference by national sovereignty, constitutional limits, individual rights or private property ownership.<p>
The MacArthur Foundation refused to respond to our inquiries.  Asked to comment on global taxes and MacArthur's grant to the Commission on Global Governance, Ray Boyer, communications director for the foundation, declared, "We choose not to do an interview with Foundation Watch."  The "no-comment" may reflect MacArthur's uneasiness over previous Capital Research Center disclosures of its activities.  CRC visiting fellow Martin Morse Wooster, in his work The Great Philanthropists & the Problem of "Donor Intent,"  described the foundation's failure to honor the intentions of its benefactor, John D. MacArthur, whose $3 billion fortune is being used to further the goals of individuals and groups for which its founder had no documented sympathy.  A champion of free enterprise, MacArthur intensely disliked government bureaucracies and regulations and opposed attempts to restrict economic development.<p>
Yet the MacArthur Foundation has underwritten groups that are dedicated to more taxes, more public spending and more regulation of the private sector.  The Institute for Policy Studies (IPS) is only the most radical example of this trend.  IPS sympathies for leftist revolutionaries, apologies for communist tyranny, and strident attacks on U.S. foreign and domestic policies were notorious before the collapse of Communism.  The current interest in "international governance" by grantmakers like MacArthur merely represents the worm's turn in new-plowed soil. The impulse to create new international bureaucracies that impose proscriptions and issue mandates is irrepressible.<p>
Direct MacArthur funding of international institutions, including the U.N. and its controversial conferences, is substantial.  For example, in 1992 the foundation directly provided $225,000 to the U.N. Office of the Secretary General "in support of United Nations Peacemaking and Peacekeeping Activities."  It gave $20,000 for the U.N. Office for Disarmament Affairs and $300,000 to the U.N. Development Program (more on this later). MacArthur gave $235,000 for the 1995 U.N. Conference in Cairo on Population and Development, where the U.N. and the Vatican wrangled over abortion policy.  It gave $102,000 for the U.N.'s 1994 Fourth World Conference on Women, held in Beijing, capital of a country that controls women's childbearing.  MacArthur also funds the U.N. Association of the United States (UNA-USA).  The premier nonprofit supporter of the United Nations received $565,400 in 1992.
Certainly the foundation's board of directors should realize that waste, fraud and abuse pervade the organization.  The November 1995 Reader's Digest provides a convenient summary of the organization's problems in an article entitled "The United Nations is Out of Control." One U.N. staffer managed to embezzle  $560,000 before getting caught.  Even Madeleine Albright, U.S Ambassador to the U.N., has admitted that she cannot "justify to the taxpayers of my country some of the personnel arrangements, the sweetheart pension deals, the lack of accountability, the waste of resources, the duplication of effort and the lack of attention to the bottom line that we often see around here."<p>
In spite of such problems, the MacArthur Foundation's committment to international governance reflects unquestioning support for the U.N., its agencies, and their mission.  As described in MacArthur's 1994 annual report, the promotion of international governance means "encouraging attention to transnational relations, multilateral agreements, and international institutions crucial to managing and mediating future conflicts."<p>

<h4>MACARTHUR'S  GLOBAL I.R.S. IN YOUR FUTURE</h4>
In 1993 the MacArthur Foundation gave $500,000 to the peculiarly-named Commission on Global Governance. This private group also received financing from foreign governments, including the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, Canada, Denmark, India, Indonesia, and Switzerland.  The government of Japan arranged for the Commission to receive funding from "two United Nations trust funds."
Of 28 members on the Commission, two are Americans:  Barber Conable, the former World Bank president who was earlier a Republican congressman from New York, and Adele Simmons, president of the MacArthur Foundation. [See box] The Commission was charged with conducting an "in-depth review of institutions involved in global and regional cooperation."  From September 1992 to October 1994 it held a series of meetings which resulted in an extraordinary report entitled "Our Global Neighborhood."  If implemented, the report's recommendations would end national sovereignty as we know it.  "In certain areas," the report argues, "sovereignty must be exercised collectively, particularly in relation to the global commons."<p>
Most of the 410 page report discusses ways of strengthening U.N. authority in world affairs, such as by creating a U.N.-sponsored criminal court. The Commission on Global Governance is quite straightforward in explaining how these activities will be financed.  It declares that global taxation will be required.  The summary of "Our Global Neighborhood" announces:
<blockquote><i>It is time for a consensus on global taxation for servicing the needs of the global neighborhood.  A start must be made in establishing schemes of global financing of global purposes, including charges on the use of global resources such as flight-lanes, sea lanes, and ocean fishing areas and the collection of revenues agreed globally and implemented by treaty.  An international tax on foreign currency transactions should be explored as one option, as should the creation of an international corporate tax base among multinational corporations.</i></blockquote>
The section which deals with global taxes is only five pages long.  However, these pages are the most explosive.  Americans should take a particular interest in this section.  Our nation was born from a tax revolt and we can be expected to bear the major burden of the Commission's tax schemes. Conscious of this history, the Commission warns that it will not be easy to enact global taxes.  Taxes are generally unpopular and, the Commission observes, "even a tightly knit group such as the European Union  has not advanced far in tax raising powers."  But aware also of the example of the successes of the international environmental movement and the proliferation of U.N. peacekeeping missions around the world, the Commission voices the hope that: 
<blockquote><i>The time could be right, however, for a fresh look and a breakthrough in this area.  The idea of safeguarding and managing the global commons -- particularly those related to the physical environment -- is now widely accepted; this cannot happen with a drip-feed approach to financing.  And the notion of expanding the role of the United Nations is now accepted in relation to military security.</i></blockquote>

<h4>DOES 'INTERNATIONAL GOVERNANCE' MEAN WORLD GOVERNMENT?</h4>
The Commission indicates that it does not favor locating the taxing power within the U.N.  It prefers instead a system by which member states would adopt a treaty or convention to impose taxes worldwide.  Yet it urges that proposals for global taxes be "initiated in the UN system" and negotiated and approved by the U.N. General Assembly before member-states ratify them through an international agreement. Once the specific recommendations of the Commission are understood, the terms "international governance" and "global goverance" make sense.  "International governance" doesn't have the clarity of "world government," but it means the same thing.<p>
In a January 1996 BBC interview U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali publicly embraced global taxation.  He advocated a "light international tax" to pay for U.N. operations.  Such a tax would give the organization "independence."  The Secretary-General declared, "I will not be under the daily financial will of the Member States."  Asked whether the tax was likely, he replied, "It takes time.  I am sure that we will win in the end and that we will obtain from the international community [recognition] that we need to have our own income."<p>
Boutros-Ghali provided additional detail in a January 1996 lecture at Oxford University.  In order for the U.N. to "operate on a secure and steady independent financial foundation," he proposed "measures for consideration."  These included a fee on speculative international financial transactions, a levy on fossil fuel use or its pollution; a small earmarked portion of the anticipated decline in world military expenditures; a stamp tax on international travel and travel documents; or a separate levy on global currency transactions.  Boutros-Ghali added, "Finding the right formula will be a project of vast importance for the future of the international community.  It will be the role of the Secretary General to bring this project to successful fruition in the twenty-first century."
The report of the Commission on Global Governance is careful to deny that global taxes to fund U.N. operations constitutes world government.  "As this report makes clear," declared Commission co-chairmen, Sir Shridath Ramphal, former Secretary-General of the [formerly British] Commonwealth, and Ingvar Carlsson, Prime Minister of Sweden, in their foreword to the document, "global governance is not global government.  No misunderstanding should arise from the similarity of the terms."  But Richard Hudson, executive director of the Center for War/Peace Studies, is skeptical.  The disclaimer, he suspects, masks the real potential that the U.N. and its associated agencies can become instruments of world government.  Hudson, editor of the group's Global Report, wrote, "The possibility of a rational debate on the issue of 'world government' has been muddied in the past few years by the introduction into the international dialogue of the term 'global governance' by the Commission on Global Governance."<p>
Hudson said he asked one-time senior U.N. official Sir Brian Urquhart, a member of the Commission, what "global governance" meant.  Urquhart responded, "Nobody knows what it means.  I was opposed to that name and suggested instead something like Commission on Global Management.  The term governance doesn't even exist in French or Spanish."<p>
Hudson says he suggested to Commission co-chairman Ramphal that "global governance" was an oxymoron for "global government" and that Ramphal replied, "Well, maybe we need some oxymorons."  Hudson may have confused a euphemism for an oxymoron, but his point was understood.  If MacArthur President Adele Simmons and the other members of the Commission on Global Governance believe in world government, shouldn't they say so?  Their report calls for global taxes and a World Court which will have compulsory jurisdiction over the nations of the world.  Unfortunately, MacArthur Foundation communications director Ray Boyer refuses to discuss the matter with Foundation Watch.<p>

<h4>BUILDING INTERNATIONAL SUPPORT FOR GLOBAL TAXATION</h4>
The U.N. has been more forthcoming about its ideas.  Peter Hansen, the former executive director of the MacArthur-funded Commission, was named U.N. Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs under Boutros-Ghali.  In this capacity, Hansen gave a presentation last September before a pro-U.N. group, the National Assembly on the United Nations and the U.S.  His talk, "Alternative Sources of Financing the UN System," described ideas for new "money raising approaches" for the U.N. as "very, very persuasive," and he favorably cited proposals for a carbon tax and a tax on international currency transactions. "It is time to take some action here," he declared. Even before Boutros-Ghali's public statements endorsing global taxes, economist Jan Tinbergen was writing in a 1994 Human Development Report of the U.N. Development Program (UNDP), "Mankind's problems can no longer be solved by national governments.  What is needed is a World Government."  Tinbergen added, "This can best be achieved by strengthening the United Nations system."<P>
The head of the UNDP is James Gustave Speth.  As president of the nonprofit World Resources Institute and a member of Bill Clinton's transition team, Speth coordinated the incoming Administration's environmental appointments.  In 1982 he founded WRI with the help of a $15,000,000 grant from  the MacArthur Foundation. In the fall of 1994 UNDP administrator Speth endorsed global taxation.  Anticipating the March 1995 U.N.-sponsored World Summit for Social Development to be held in Copenhagen, Speth declared in a speech:
<blockquote><i>Indeed, we have a unique opportunity to strike some new global compacts in the Social Summit next year in Copenhagen.  The [1994 UNDP Human Development] Report offers several concrete proposals...A global human security fund -- financed from global fees such as the 'Tobin tax' on speculative movements of international funds, an international tax on the consumption of non-renewable energy, global environmental permits and a tax on arms trade...These proposals demand a great deal from the international community.  But they are all doable.</i></blockquote>
The 1994 Human Development Report, issued by Speth's UNDP, was explicit.  It said:
<blockquote><i>...[A] serious search should begin for new sources of international funding that do not rely entirely on the fluctuating political will of the rich nations.  Global taxation may become necessary in any case to achieve the goals of global human security.  Some of the promising new sources include tradable permits for global pollution, a global tax on non-renewable energy, demilitarization funds and a small transaction tax on speculative international movements of foreign exchange funds.</i></blockquote>
The 1994 Human Development Report went even further.  It added details on the taxes on energy and international currency transactions that it proposed: 
<blockquote><i>A second logical source of funds for a global response to global threats is a set of fees on globally important transactions or polluting emissions....One is a tax on the international movements of speculative capital suggested by James Tobin, winner of the Nobel Prize for Economics....[It] could raise $150 billion a year...Another is a global tax on energy: a tax of $1 on each barrel of oil (and its equivalent on coal) during 1995-2000 would yield around $66 billion a year.</i></blockquote>

<h4>THE TOBIN TAX</h4>
The 1994 Human Development Report featured an article by James Tobin, winner of the 1981 Nobel Prize for Economics.  Tobin estimated that his proposal could produce revenues of $1.5 trillion a year: 
<blockquote><i>An international uniform tax would be levied on spot transactions in foreign exchange...The revenue potential is immense, over $1.5 trillion a year for the 0.5% tax...It is appropriate that the proceeds of an international tax be devoted to international purposes and be placed at the disposal of international institutions.</i></blockquote>
Proposals for global taxes were seriously offered and debated  at the March 1995  World Summit for Social Development in Copenhagen.  One leading proponent was France's late president, Socialist Francois Mitterand, who spoke to the conference just a few months before his death.  <i>The New York Times</i> reported, "He supported a proposal to tax speculative international currency transactions as [a] way of raising money for development...President Mitterand...said he had no illusions about the difficulty of establishing a tax on financial transactions.  But he challenged the audience of more than 115 government leaders to make a real commitment." <i>The Washington Post</i> also took note of the "Tobin Tax":  "Another idea, proposed by James Tobin, an American who won the Nobel Prize for economics in 1981, called for a tax on speculative currency transfers to raise funds for development aid.  A tax on short-term currency deals as small as 0.05 percent, U.N. officials say, could raise as much as $150 billion a year  and produce the added benefit of discouraging disruptive financial speculation." <P>
	The UNDP's follow-up 1995 Human Development Report referred to the ongoing "global human development debate" which had led to "concrete policy proposals" on taxes.  It added that these include "finding new sources of funding for global human security, such as the 'Tobin Tax' on international speculative movements of currency or internationally tradable permits for global emissions. At the recent World Summit for Social Development, proposals such as the 20:20 compact [a proposal for international financial assistance to poor countries] and the Tobin tax attracted widespread interest from many quarters." In an April 1995 article endorsing global taxes in <i>Choices</i>, the official organ of the UNDP, UNDP historian Ruben Mendez proposes a variation on the Tobin tax.  He urges that a "Foreign Currency Exchange" be established as a U.N. agency to "generate vast revenues" for the world body and declares, "It is time to make an intellectual quantum leap, and to look beyond the nation-state for new, innovative and independent transnational sources of funds."<P>
	Mendez had earlier endorsed the Tobin Tax in a 1993 report to the Commission on Global Governance.  But in the 1995 article he expressed his fear that the Tobin Tax was unworkable because "formidable obstacles stand in its way."  He explained, "Foreign exchange transactions are often loose and informal.  They leave no 'paper trail' by which they can be monitored and taxed." By contrast, Mendez' "Foreign Currency Exchange" (FXE) would operate as foreign securities exchanges do, but by offering lower rates they would be less expensive.  The FXE would be a "publicly-owned entity" run by the U.N.  A 1.0 percent rate for fees and commissions could generate $840 million a day, he claimed. Former <i>Forbes</i> magazine staff reporter Steven Solomon provides another variation on the theme in his book <i>The Confidence Game</i> (Simon & Schuster, 1995).  Solomon urges formation of a "world economic directorate" to manage national economies and adoption of a global tax on international currency transactions.  The Solomon version brings in $13 trillion a year.<P>
	"Such great sums," he enthuses, "could be used to pay the cost of administering new financial regulations.  Some could be turned over to the Basel club [i.e. central bankers] to pursue interventions to stabilize currencies and to carry out lender of last resort missions.  Some could finance the World Bank for economic development, or an IMF that might be restructured to evolve into a world central bank and seat of a genuine world economic directorate."  In a footnote, Solomon acknowledges that his proposal is a variation of the Tobin Tax.<P>

<h4>MORE CLEVER TAX SCHEMES</h4>
Because foundations understand that no single commission or report is adequate to build support for political change, they fund a variety of approaches.  The Ford Foundation, for instance, which contributed to the support of the Commission on Global Governance, also subsidized a 1994 study, <i>Renewing the United Nations System</i>, by former U.N. officials Erskine Childers and Brian Urquhart, a Commission member. Their report notes that "a range of international taxation schemes" have been proposed, including a "United Nations surcharge" on arms sales, land-mines, the international movement of currencies, international trade, international air and sea travel, and the production of materials such as petroleum and hydro-carbons, and raw mineral commodities.  Despite their sympathy for global tax proposals, Childers and Urquhart acknowledge that, "Schemes for additional financing of the UN are...easy to suggest but would not be at all easy to implement."  Nonetheless, they cannot stop themselves from making an additional proposal to designate: <i>one day in each year as 'United Nations Communication Day,' when all postage charges and telephone calls (and a fraction of broadcasting advertising revenues?) would carry levies accruing to the UN, with special public information on the world organization.</i><P>
Childers and Urquhart realistically warn that for all global tax proposals, "Each member-government would have to agree to levy any such taxes, and collect and transfer them to approved parts of the UN System.  Thus, international taxation revenue would essentially rise through and stay under the control of member-governments."  Cleverly, they devise an alternative that has worked for state governments and Indian tribes, and propose an annual "United Nations lottery, administered by a special authority under the Secretary-General," and licensed by member-states.<P>
It would be a mistake to dismiss these ideas with ridicule or to assume that they are purely hypothetical.  In one key area the U.N. already has made progress in securing global taxing authority.  The Law of the Sea Treaty provides for a precedent-setting Seabed Authority.  As the MacArthur-funded United Nations Association (UNA-USA) notes, "Only the Seabed Authority created by the U.N. Convention on the Law of the Sea, which entered into force in late 1994, has authority today to directly collect international revenues to finance its activities."  The treaty, to which the U.S. is not yet a party, is awaiting U.S. Senate ratification and its prospects are uncertain.<P>

<h4>WHAT SHOULD AMERICA DO?</h4>
One should not take comfort in the belief that Senate ratification of international treaties is a fool-proof block against global taxes.  The U.N. Charter is not entirely clear about how the organization will be financed.  Article 17 only says that the General Assembly should consider and approve the budget of the organization and that the expenses "shall be borne by the Members as apportioned by the General Assembly."  Moreover, the third part of Article 17 says that the General Assembly "shall consider and approve any  financial and budgetary arrangements with specialized agencies..." And Article 29 says "The Security Council may establish such subsidiary organs as it deems necessary for the performance of its functions."  These might well be tax-raising agencies and they conceivably could be established by a vote of the permanent members of the Security Council.<P>
Fortunately, the U.S. Constitution remains a bulwark against bureaucratic inventiveness.  Even if the Executive branch supported a Security Council proposal and even if the U.S. Senate ratified an international treaty, the Constitution says bills to raise taxes must originate in the U.S. House of Representatives.  At least for the moment, it is unlikely that the House will listen to foundation grantmakers and international bureaucrats on this issue. In 1996 now Republican Presidential contender Bob Dole and Senators Jesse Helms and Judd Gregg formally requested the General Accounting Office (GAO) investigate the status of these proposals.  Congressional hearings have been promised by Senator Helms.  The Senators threatened legislation to cut off all funds to the U.N. if the world body attempts to implement global taxes.<P>
The reaction of the Clinton Administration has been fascinating and yet predictable.  Quickly responding to the Boutros-Ghali speech, the State Department issued a strong statement through spokesman Nicholas Burns headlined: "U.S. Opposition to Worldwide Tax to Support the U.N."  It said: 
<blockquote><i>The United Nations does not have the authority to impose or collect any form of tax, and the U.S. Government would not consent to any proposal to grant it such authority. The United States continues to believe that the best way to ensure adequate and predictable funding for the United Nations system is through reforms which result in a fair system of financing, and which reduce overall costs and allow reinvestments of savings in areas of high priority to member states.  An approach to fundraising that involved any form of international tax would be inconsistent with the intergovernmental nature of the organization and could undermine the sovereignty of member states.</i></blockquote>
The Clinton Administration is now on the public  record opposing Boutros-Ghali's proposal for global taxes. But there is no hint here that one of the Administration's top people at the UN, James Gustave Speth,  favors just that initiative.<P>
As head of the U.N. Development Program, Gus Speth has been encouraging the global tax schemes that the State Department says it opposes.  Speth was appointed to his U.N. post at the urging of the Clinton administration. Luckily, the United States is still a constitutional republic, and despite the best efforts of the MacArthur Foundation, the prospect of increasing taxes to pay for the United Nations runs counter to the tax-cutting message of this year's presidential campaign. The anti-tax feeling among the American citizenry is not hard to understand.  And apparently growing opposition to Boutros-Ghali in the U.N. might also delay the establishment of an international  I.R.S. This is understandable. Imagine the reaction of the MacArthur Foundation if someone were to propose a hefty levy on tax-exempt foundations to support a  project of which it apparently did not approve -- such as strengthening American sovereignty.<P>
