<HEAD>

<TITLE>Organizational Trends - April, 1996 - CRC</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center><img src="/crc/images/hdr-ot.gif" alt="Organizational Trends"></center>
<P>
<i>April, 1996</i>
<P>
<h2>The Sentencing Project</h2>
<P>
<I><B>
Crime, Race and Federal Funding</B></I>
<P>
<a href="#race">Race and Imprisonment: What's the Connection?</a><br>
<a href="#crime">To Let the Punishment Fit the Crime </a><br>
<a href="#answ">Bad Answers to Foolish Questions</a><br>
<a href="#edna">Sources of Funding:  The Edna McConnell Clark Foundation</a><br>
<a href="#fund">Federal Government Funding</a><p>

Pick up any news article about crime and somewhere in it you are likely to come across a reference to the  
Sentencing Project, a little known Washington, D.C. think tank which focuses on crime issues.  A Nexis  
search reveals that the group's name has appeared in 219 stories, 71 of them since the start of last year.  <p>
  Although obviously a press darling, the Sentencing Project (TSP) is unlike other Washington think tanks.   
It has none of the glitz of better-known policy groups:  no fancy offices or panelled conference rooms or  
glossy annual report.  What is remarkable about TSP's success is that it promotes its agenda while  
remaining obscure as an organization.  <p>
  Housed in a run-down part of Washington around the corner from the tour buses parked outside Ford's  
Theater, the group promotes what it calls "alternative sentencing programs."  From dingy offices reached  
by an antique elevator, it issues a stream of reports and policy papers whose titles - "Building Alternatives  
Instead of Jails"; "Racial Disparity in `Crack' Cocaine Sentencing"; and "Why `3 Strikes and You're Out'  
Won't Reduce Crime" - remind the reader that the absence of subtlety or nuance is not an invention of talk  
radio.  <p>
  These reports generally hammer away at two points.  The first is that locking up criminals does not reduce  
crime.  The second is that the criminal justice system is rigged against racial minorities.  These conclusions  
find their way to the front pages of major newspapers, the evening television news broadcasts, and the  
speeches of politicians.  <p>
  TSP is virtually a conservative caricature of liberal crime policy.  Rather than focus on the finding of guilt  
and the appropriate punishment for criminal acts, it seeks to uncover the sociology of "root causes" of  
crime.  And it attacks the political motivations of those who favor penalizing criminal behavior.  What is  
astounding is that we are paying for TSP.  The nonprofit 501(c)(3) group is funded through a "major grant"  
from the Department of Justice's Bureau of Justice Assistance.  <p>
  TSP was founded in 1986 by Malcolm C. Young, who had been associated with the National Council on  
Crime and Delinquency, another liberal crime group.  Young remains TSP's Executive Director.  Assistant  
Director Marc Mauer is its chief spokesman and he writes many TSP reports.  <p>  
  Although most people would consider TSP's notions of justice to be marginal and even kooky, the group  
is not without influence in the criminal law arena, where liberal judges, criminal defense attorneys, and law  
professors continue to take these ideas seriously.  TSP in 1992 increased its visibility by establishing a  
professional association, the National Association of Sentencing Advocates.  TSP also runs the Campaign  
for an Effective Crime Policy, a coalition of "criminal justice professionals" working against  
"demagoguery on crime."  <p>
   Public faith in the criminal justice system has been strained for some time.  Doubts about the system's  
fairness have fueled citizen disgust with political leaders who seem more concerned about the procedural  <p>
rights of criminals than with the suffering of their victims.  How can public confidence be restored when  
tax money is used to finance the advocates of the very policies which provoke the mistrust?  Is it any  
wonder the public is angry?   <p>
  
<a name="race"><b>Race and Imprisonment: What's the Connection?</b></a>  <p>
  The Sentencing Project is best known for its much-publicized work on the nexis between race and  
incarceration.  In 1995, the group released a study which showed one in every three black men between the  
ages of 20 to 29 was under the supervision of the criminal justice system:  either in jail or prison, or on  
parole or probation.  Entitled Young Black Americans and the Criminal Justice System, the study was  
reported in virtually every major media outlet, including the New York Times, Washington Post, Los  
Angeles Times, CNN, and National Public Radio.  Jesse Jackson invoked it during his speech at the  
"Million Man March" in Washington.    <p>
  One major finding of the report is that the war on drugs has a disproportionate impact on minorities.  It  
concludes that the effort by law enforcement authorities to stamp out illegal drugs and various proposals to  
get tough on crime are contributing to a "growing racial disparity in the criminal justice system."  Indeed, it  
claims that the war on drugs has been an "unmitigated disaster" for young blacks.  <p>
  TSP blames the increase in the number of blacks in the criminal justice system on what it sees as a  
lopsided emphasis on convictions relating to crack cocaine.  It attributes this to "police practices that target  
inner-city communities for intensive drug enforcement. . . ."  <p>
  TSP's illogical evasion of responsibility is evident when it blames not drugs but the war on drugs for the  
destruction of a generation of young black males.  Crack cocaine is destructive.  The evidence shows that  
violence is associated with crack cocaine far more than with the powder variety.  As social policy expert  
Douglas Besharov of the American Enterprise Institute has observed:  "The evidence is quite clear . . .  
Crack is a more addictive, violence-creating drug than is powder cocaine.  Period."  <p>
  Underlying TSP's report is the belief that many of those convicted and sent to prison are low-level drug  
offenders who do not pose a threat to society.  However, as Princeton Professor and crime expert John  
DiIulio noted recently in the Washington Post, "virtually all drug offenders behind bars are in for drug  
trafficking, not mere possession" _ and most "have long criminal records."  Says DiIulio, "anyone who  
thinks U.S. attorneys or big-city cops focus their enforcement energies against petty drug criminals must be  
either statistically illiterate or smoking something."  <p>
  The black community has indeed suffered from the scourge of crack cocaine.  But this argues for greater  
vigilance in stamping out its sale and use.  Black families will suffer most from any slackening of law  
enforcement.  While TSP argues that the war on drugs serves to "exacerbate" racial "inequities," its  
solution is to go easy on the drug criminals who devastate inner-city communities.    <p>
  TSP Assistant Director Marc Mauer proposes a "renewed dialogue on drug policy."  He notes obliquely  
that the disciplining of former Surgeon General Joycelyn Elders "for advocating a discussion of drug  
policy" indicated a lack of "serious discussion" about substance abuse.  Elders was talking about legalizing  
drugs, and Mauer's euphemistic call for "dialogue" is nothing more than an excuse for starting down the  
road toward drug legalization.    <p>
  TSP's policy research has usefully documented how drug crimes have led to the imprisonment of all too  
many young black men.  But it is tragic for the black community that this research should result in such  
misguided policy recommendations.  These proposals should make the public wary of "policy experts" who  
claim to know the significance of their own findings.  
  <p>
<a name="crime"><b>To Let the Punishment Fit the Crime </b> </a><p>
  TSP's ideas about race and the criminal justice system follow from the group's premise that incarceration  
just doesn't work and that it's simply not an enlightened way to deal with persons convicted of crimes.  The  
group opposes mandatory minimum sentences and "three-strikes-and-you're-out" proposals that require life  
sentences for three-time violent offenders.  TSP says the latter are "harsh" and "divert public attention from  
a full discussion of the causes of violent crime."  Likewise, it opposes truth in sentencing measures that  
restrict parole, and it is hostile to just about anything that increases the penalty for committing a crime. <p> 
  TSP dismisses attempts to introduce greater accountability in criminal law and certainty in sentencing as  
unsophisticated responses to the public's alarm over crime.  It also denigrates them as a way for politicians  
to exploit middle class hysteria.  In 1994, Mauer told the press, "Part of what is driving this [effort to crack  
down on crime] is politicians' simplistic approach to dealing with crime and part is suburban America's  
fears."  <p>  
  Testifying before Congress in 1994, Mauer said that incarceration "has a limited impact on crime" and  
there is no "clear relationship between crime and incarceration."  But if keeping criminals out of prison  
does not increase crime rates one might as well believe that keeping Congress in session will not lead to  
more laws.<p>    
  The Council on Crime in America, a project of the New Citizenship Project, has demonstrated the relation  
of crime and punishment in a recently published study entitled The State of Violent Crime in America.  It  
takes note of the "obvious reality that prisons restrain convicted criminals from committing large numbers  
of crimes that they would be committing if free."  In other words, much serious crime is averted each year  
by keeping convicted criminals behind bars.  The report cites a number of empirical studies which estimate  
that for each additional incarcerated felon, anywhere from 12 to 17 additional crimes will not be committed  
each year.  <p>   
  Moreover, by applying 1973 crime rates to the 1989 population, the report estimates that there were  
60,000 fewer rapes, 323,000 fewer robberies, and 380,000 fewer assaults in 1989.  In other words, contrary  
to the assertions of TSP, increasing the prison population in the 1980s significantly reduced violent crime  
below what it would have otherwise been.  (This is not to suggest that one should take heart about the  
current crime situation; only that it could have been much worse.) <p> 
  This is common sense to most people, but not to TSP, which insists that increasing the number of prisons  
and prisoners has had no effect.  As the Council report observed, "It apparently takes a Ph.D. in  
criminology to doubt that if we released half of all prisoners tonight, we would experience more crime  
tomorrow."<p>  
  Another recent study, this one conducted by the Dallas-based National Center for Policy Analysis,  
bolsters these conclusions.  Focusing on crime in Texas, the report demonstrates how a more aggressive  
incarceration policy has lead to a dramatic reduction in the state's crime rate.  According to the study, the  
overall rate of serious crime in Texas has been cut by 35 percent and is at its lowest level since 1973.  This  
follows a four-year building boom, which has raised prison capacity from 49,000 to 150,000, with the  
state's prison population increasing to 64 percent above the national average.  The data is also interesting in  
that it refutes TSP's mantra that longer sentences do not deter crime:  In Texas, the average time served for  
serious crimes climbed from 1.9 years to 3 years.  <p>
  While TSP argues that prison is a failure, the evidence from the states paints a different picture.  Yet to  
the true believer facts are irrelevant; and TSP remains undaunted.  Not only does it reject the proposition  
that putting criminals in prison reduces crime, it also contends that increasing the number of police will not  
bring the crime rate down.  "There is little relationship between the number of police per capita and crime  
rates," Mauer wrote in a 1994 USA Today op-ed.   
  <p>
<a name="answ"><b>Bad Answers to Foolish Questions</b></a><p>	  
TSP is preoccupied with explaining the "causes" of crime.   
Predictably, it blames the failures on society.  This familiar refrain condemns "abuse and neglect" for crime  
and censures "attitudes toward women" and "the ready availability of firearms in this country" for violence.   
In Mauer's view, "incarceration speaks very little to poor schooling, dysfunctional families, or limited job  
skills."  <p>
  What then is the answer?  More government spending.  TSP wants to spend tax dollars not on stopping  
crimes or catching criminals, but on social programs for more treatment and counseling, for education and  
recreation.  Mauer testified that "programs such as Head Start and Job Corps are cost effective in reducing  
long-term crime control costs."  Washington liberals conclude that every ill plaguing society can be cured  
by a government program; crime is no exception.    <p>
  Mauer actually has gone so far as to suggest that Hillary Clinton's health care task force should serve as a  
"model" for how the country should approach crime policy.  He noted approvingly that President Clinton  
"assembled a team of hundreds of experts to dissect and analyze every aspect of the health care system. . .  
."  And he wondered why there has been no parallel effort with respect to crime.  (Hint:  Hillary's task force  
was a failure!)  TSP sees this as part of a "more rational and humane" approach to crime.  Given the voters'  
revulsion at Mrs. Clinton's health care machinations, what could be more cruel?  <p>
  Former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese, a Capital Research Center trustee, says TSP operates in a  
"fantasy world."  "Of course crime reflects deeper societal problems," adds Meese, "but that doesn't answer  
the question of what to do about the criminals on the streets right now.  How do we keep known criminals  
from committing more crimes?"  The answer is to "put them where they can no longer harm others _ in  
prison."  <p>
  
<a name="edna"><b>Sources of Funding:  The Edna McConnell Clark Foundation</b></a>  <p>
  TSP reflects the world-view of its benefactor, the Edna McConnell Clark Foundation, a prime patron of  
left-wing causes from the ACLU to the Children's Defense Fund.  With assets of $500 million, the Clark  
Foundation is one of America's largest foundations.  Mrs. Clark's father was the founder of Avon Products,  
and her husband, with whom she established the Foundation in 1950, was chairman of the board of the  
cosmetics business.  The Foundation is unrelated to the Robert Sterling Clark Foundation (see April  
Foundation Watch).   <p>
  Like TSP, the Foundation wants to "move the corrections system away from an overreliance on jails and  
prisons."  Its annual report repeats the buzz phrases of anti-incarceration advocates:  "community-based  
punishments"; "inadequate investment"; "intermediate punishments"; "unnecessary incarceration";  
"nonviolent offenders"; and "alternatives."    <p>
  In 1994 TSP received three grants from the Clark Foundation totaling $195,271.  The year before the  
Foundation awarded TSP two grants totaling $334,000.  Besides providing financial backing to TSP, the  
Clark Foundation's Program for Justice also supports the Families Against Mandatory Minimums  
Foundation, which opposes laws setting minimum sentences for various crimes.  It also funds the American  
Civil Liberties Union's National Prison Project, awarding it $825,000 in 1994.  The National Prison Project  
is a prisoners' "rights" organization that litigates on behalf of incarcerated criminals.  <p> 
  This is elitism at its worst.  The folks at TSP and the Clark Foundation can win kudos from academics by  
theorizing about alternatives to prison.  But the urban poor who must suffer the consequences of crime as  
well as the consequences of naive crime policies have no such luxury.  They are not interested in  
speculating about root causes.  Instead, they want to see criminals swept from the streets.    
<p><a name="fund"><b>Federal Government Funding</b></a>  <p>
  TSP's private foundation funding is augmented by the federal government.  The Justice Department's  
support will enable TSP to "publish a guide for the establishment and operation of defense-based  
alternative sentencing programs."  (According to the most recent information available through FAADS,  
the federal grants database, the Justice Department awarded TSP $125,000 in the last quarter of 1993.)<p>  
  Last year, Congress failed to deal with the problem of government funding of nonprofit advocacy groups.   
Reps. Ernest Istook (R-OK), David McIntosh (R-IN) and Robert Ehrlich (R-MD) were unable to convince  
their colleagues that federal grants should not be given to nonprofit groups engaged in political advocacy.   
But TSP illustrates why action on this front is needed now more than ever.  You wouldn't know it by  
visiting its offices, but TSP is one of the most influential players in the ongoing debate about crime.   
Regrettably, it is the kind of influence we could do without.  <p>
  Media and political elites bemoan what they characterize as public cynicism toward government  
institutions.  They should not be so perplexed.  What else can one expect when citizens discover that their  
tax dollars are squandered so foolishly?  The public demands protection from crime, yet finds its money  
spent on those whose solution is keep criminals out of jail.  

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
