<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Philanthropy, Culture & Society -- CRC</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center><img src="/crc/images/hdr-pcs.gif" alt="Philanthropy, Culture & Society"></center>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=4>March 1996</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<h2>Rediscovering Heroes, Remembering Dreams
Rediscovering Heroes, Remembering Dreams<p></h2>
<b><I>A Challenge to Change Lives</I></b><BR>
<p>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>By Marvin Olasky</FONT></B>
<P>

&nbsp;&nbsp;My goal today is to help each of you think more clearly
about the welfare problem so that you become an agent of change.
Our emphasis should be on change that moves people out of poverty.
We should not be agents of spare change, the distribution of which
merely enables people to stay in poverty. Many citizens today
are agents of spare change.  They hand out quarters or dollars
at street corners with good intentions and support more federal
welfare spending.  Those intentions are often reflected in church
bulletin announcements about the homeless.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Here are a few of those announcements that have been
brought to my attention: First: &quot;Thursday night... Dinner
for the homeless.  Meditation to follow.&quot; Here's another:
&quot;At the evening service tonight, the sermon topic will be
'Seeing Hell close-up...Come early to meet homeless visitors.&quot;
One more: &quot;Don't let homelessness kill you...let the church
help.&quot; 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;These are honest mistakes, but they show why we must
go beyond sentimentality and learn how to fight poverty the right
way, the biblical way, the way that was practiced in America until
recent decades.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;A large part of our current problem arises from the
twisting of Scripture.  If a supporter of the contemporary welfare
state were to rewrite the parable of the prodigal son, he might
write something like this: &quot;One young man set off for a distant
country and there squandered his wealth in wild living.  After
he had spent everything, he was in need and took a job feeding
pigs. The job was miserable, and the man visualized an alternative:
'I will go back to my father and say to him: Father, I have sinned.'
He was about to return  home, but an official from  Beds for
the Homeless saw him and convinced him to spend the night.  The
shelter offered free food, housing, clothing, and medicine, and
did not require any work in return.  The prodigal son stayed on
and became used to panhandling in the morning, drinking fortified
wine and smoking some joints in the afternoon, and watching movies
at the shelter in the evening.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&quot;Meanwhile, the father sat on his porch in the
late afternoon, hoping to see the prodigal son trudging home.
Day after day the father yearned for the opportunity to hug him
and prepare a feast, but the son never came.&quot; 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;That's the tale of the prodigal panhandler, and I
could give you other brand new revised version stories. One of
my favorites is, &quot;Jesus Food Stamps the 5000.&quot;  The
Bible is where we learn how to provide effective compassion for
prodigals.  That God created each of us in His own image, and
that He provided for us a way to be delivered from our inclination
to deface his image, underlies everything I say here.<BR>

<P>
<H3>Forgotten Heroes</H3>

&nbsp;&nbsp;Here are the two propositions I would like to put
before you:  First, the reason why government welfare programs
must be transformed is not that they are too expensive.  The real
problem is that they are too stingy about doing what is truly
important: treating people as human beings made in God's image,
not as animals to be fed, caged, and occasionally petted.  Second,
private programs can do a better job if they  are challenging,
personal, and spiritual-most often, when they are religiously
based.
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Some of you have gained experience working with the
poor and I want to hear what you have learned. But I'm speaking
to you after having spent a year in the bowels of the Library
of Congress searching through old records.  I'm here today to
testify to the work of many people forgotten by the standard history
books-men like Charles Brace.  Over a 40-year period Brace built
lodging houses in New York City that provided shelter to several
hundred thousand abandoned children.   He placed 91,000 of them
in adoptive homes.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Women like Helen Mercy Woods.  From 1881 to 1903 she
ran a shelter in Chicago for pregnant and unmarried women.  Month
after month she gave personal attention to each newcomer and rejoiced
as their babies were born. She helped some of her charges to get
married, others to place their children for adoption, others to
get jobs.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;I'm here to testify about now-forgotten heroes like
Annie Richardson Kennedy.  She ran a home for unwed moms in New
York City between 1900 and 1920.  Her goal was to first bring
the girls in touch with their Savior, and then build character.
She provided love and opportunity for thousands, and then disappeared
into the fog of history. When I visited the site of her shelter
several years ago, it was occupied by the consulate of Yemen.
The guard didn't understand much English, and I was not making
his day when I asked him if anyone knew what had happened to a
home for mothers and babies that was there 70 years before. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;My wife doesn't mind when I fall in love with women
like Helen Mercy Woods and Annie Richardson Kennedy, because they've
all been dead for a long time. The textbooks are silent, but I'm
here to testify about the contributions they made.
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;You might think that the work of an historian is boring,
but it's exciting detective work to blow dust off old reports
in the Library of Congress and learn about people who changed
so many lives for the better.  It may be an acquired taste to
sit in the Chicago Historical Society and read the diaries of
self-sacrificing people hour after hour, until the librarian there
turns off the lights and kicks you out, but it's exciting to uncover
what secular liberal historians ignore. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;The big story that they missed is this:  During the
19th century, before the federal government ever got involved,
a war on poverty much more successful than our own was waged
by tens of thousands of local, private charitable agencies and
religious groups around the country. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;It was successful in this way: poverty fighters a
century ago did not abolish poverty, but they witnessed movement
out of poverty by millions of people. Successful in this way:
There were springs of fresh water flowing among the poor, not
just blocks of ice sitting in a perpetual winter of multigenerational
welfare dependency.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Successful also in this way: The optimism prevalent
then contrasts sharply with the demoralization among the poor
and the cynicism among the better-off that is so common now. I'm
here to testify that there was a great cloud of witnesses to effective
poverty-fighting, and that they succeeded in large ways by knowing
and doing small but vital things. They knew that the literal meaning
of compassion is not just writing a check, but having personal
involvement with the needy, suffering with them, not just giving
money to them. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;They knew that welfare doesn't mean passing a bill,
but helping a person to fare well. They knew that the Constitution
talks about providing for the common defense but promoting the
general welfare-and there's a big difference between renting a
hall for a convention, and manning every booth yourself. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;They knew that people should be challenged. When an
able-bodied man came to a homeless shelter, he often was asked
to chop wood for two hours or to whitewash a building.  In that
way he could provide part of his own support and also help those
unable to chop. They knew, and they showed everyone through those
work tests, that even the most run-down person is not just a taker;
he can also be a giver. They knew that everyone is made in God's
image and is capable of helping. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;And they knew what to avoid: in fact, they warned
us.  Some of their warnings were amazingly prophetic. Mary Richmond
of the Baltimore Charity Organizing Society said in 1897, &quot;Relief
given without reference to friends and neighbors is accompanied
by moral loss.  Poor neighborhoods are doomed to grow poorer whenever
the natural ties of neighborliness are weakened by well-meant
but unintelligent interference.&quot;  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;The New Orleans Charity Organization Society in 1899
wisely noted, &quot;Intelligent giving and intelligent withholding
are alike true charity.&quot; Giving money to a poor person by
itself is morally neutral, because the action can hurt if not
done wisely.   New York charity leader Josephine Lowell said,
&quot;The problem before those who would be charitable, is not
how to deal with a given number of the poor; it is how to help
those who are poor, without adding to their numbers and constantly
increasing the evils they seek to cure.&quot; 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Poverty-fighters a century ago trained volunteers
to leave behind &quot;a conventional attitude toward the poor,
seeing them through the comfortable haze of our own intentions.&quot;
They said, &quot;If drink has made a man poor, money will feed
not him, but his drunkenness.&quot;  They did not use euphemisms.
They said it is  important to &quot;reform those mild, well-meaning,
tenderhearted, sweet-voiced criminals who insist upon indulging
in indiscriminate charity.&quot; They said that government payouts
come &quot;from what is regarded as a practically inexhaustible
source, and people who once receive it are likely to regard it
as a right, as a permanent pension, implying no obligation on
their part.&quot; They were prophetic!<BR>

<P>
<H3>Dream Killers</H3>

&nbsp;&nbsp;They were prophetic, but the historical knowledge
of many Americans today is pathetic.  Let me be blunt:  We don't
know much about history.  We've forgotten America's past successes
in poverty-fighting. The result has been not just the waste of
billions of dollars each year, but the death of  part of the American
dream.   
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;For a time it was considered hardheaded to talk about
dollars and corny to speak about dreams.  The debate in Washington
was always liberals wanting to spend more and conservatives wanting
to spend less, but no one questioning what welfare does to dreams.

<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;History, though, is made by dreams followed by action.
America was begun by people who resolved to fight for a country
in which both liberty and virtue could flourish.  But now, welfare
kills dreams. It kills the helping dream of many Americans.  
Most of you and millions of other people would like to be generous
when a panhandler asks for spare change.  But if you know that
most homeless recipients will use any available funds for drugs
or alcohol and will put off real change by getting high, you are
likely to end up walking by and avoiding eye contact. A subtle
hardening occurs.
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Welfare also kills the dreams of social workers. 
Their common lament is, &quot;All we have time to do is move paper.&quot;
Listen to this sad statement from a social worker who graduated
from college several years ago, lasted on the job for a year,
and then resigned: &quot;I had a calling; it was that simple.
I wanted to help.&quot;  A lot of people are frustrated, worn
down, burnt out. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Welfare also kills the dreams of poor individuals
who gradually become used to dependency.  Some among the poor
are willing to put off immediate gratification and  sacrifice
leisure time in order to remain independent, but they are called
chumps rather than champs. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Welfare kills the dreams of children who grow up without
fathers.  Coach a little league team some time and you'll quickly
see who's in that fix.  Fatherless children alternately cling
and are standoffish in a way that kids with functioning dads do
not. It breaks your heart.
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Welfare kills.  Spend some time with AFDC moms or
with homeless men.  You'll see how sad they are.  You'll see the
essential problem, and I'll stress it again:  Governmental welfare
programs should be fought not because they are too expensive,
but because they are inevitably too stingy in what is truly important:
treating people as human beings made in God's image, not as animals.

<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Should we despair?  No. I'm hear to testify that the
reams of the past can thrive in the future if we recover the
lessons of the past and use them to plan for the future. I am
finding good news as I get around the country now: We are recovering
the lost tools of charitable success.  We are  seeing a new great
cloud of witnesses.  We are living in an era with many heroes
or, I should say, ordinary people who become heroic as they show,
through hard suffering with, that the American dream of compassion
is not dead. <BR>

<P>
<H3>Modern Heroes</H3>

&nbsp;&nbsp;I wish you could come with me and visit Bob Cote in
Denver.  He's a tall, white, ex- boxer who spent a year on the
streets as an alcoholic in the early '80s and then pulled together
a few of his fellow winos and junkies to start a program that
has become known as Step 13.  Bob welcomed me to his four-story
building and showed me how  people from off the streets can, step
by step, come back to life.  They can get jobs of increasing responsibility.
They can get rooms within that building that gradually reflect
greater independence, until a person is ready to go out on his
own.  They can go through a tough, time-intensive process.  Cote
has lived it himself and he's there to help others. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;I wish you could come with me and visit Hannah Hawkins,
who lives  in Anacostia, the poorest part of Washington.  She's
short, black, and retired, and she voluntarily runs an after-school
program which has several dozen children doing their homework
and receiving the love they often don't get at home. Sometimes
they run around like lost sheep, but she knows each of her lambs
by name. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;I wish you could come with me and visit Freddie Garcia
in San Antonio.  He's a softhearted but hardheaded Hispanic ex-addict.
He formed Victory Outreach 25 years ago in San Antonio to help
substance abusers.  Groups based on his teaching have now spread
throughout Texas and California and even to Peru.  I've sat in
his home and watched the way he patiently counsels and teaches
those whom everyone else has abandoned. I've been blessed to see
and come to know some of these people, and I'm here to testify
that they have succeeded and others can too.   The heroes of past
and present have a common understanding that could be summarized
as CPS.<BR>

<P>
<H3>Challenging, Personal, and Spiritual</H3>
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;What's CPS? Compassion needs to be Challenging, Personal,
and Spiritual.  I hope it will become as well known as CPR.  
CPR can bring back to life a dying person; CPS can bring back
to life a dying American dream. &nbsp;&nbsp;People successfully
practiced CPS a century ago, and they are successfully doing it
right now.  There is compassion that is challenging, personal,
and spiritual at Clean and Sober Streets in Washington.  Leaders
there get people off drugs and alcohol by caring for them but
also imposing tough rules-one strike you're out-and sticking to
them. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;There is compassion that is challenging, personal,
and spiritual at Teen Challenge sites in Texas and around the
country, where alcoholism is treated as a symptom, not the fundamental
problem.  Leaders there know that the basic problem is that people
have holes in their souls, holes that only God can fill.
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;There is compassion that is challenging, personal,
and spiritual at the Right Alternative center in Milwaukee. People
sometimes say that AFDC mothers will be stuck on the government
rolls for a life time, but at Right Alternative AFDC moms pledge
not to swear, not to shack up, not to do drugs.  Leaders there
challenge them to stick to their pledges, and when they do their
lives change:  They do get married.  They do get jobs. What works?
Challenging help... Personal help... Spiritual help. It worked
in the past.  It works now.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;The evidence of changed lives is accumulating. I'm
not saying it's easy.  I've personally seen successes over the
years. I've seen lives of pregnant unmarried women turned around.
I've seen abandoned children happily adopted.  I've also seen
failures:  Recently I was working with a homeless ex-con, and
I thought he was making good progress, but he slipped back into
irresponsibility.  He's currently in a jail facility near Fort
Worth, but he'll have another chance in several months.<BR>

<P>
<H3>Answering Five Criticisms</H3>

&nbsp;&nbsp;I don't want anyone to go into poverty-fighting without
understanding the difficulties.  In fact, let me give you my responses
to five  criticisms of the generally optimistic message I'm offering
tonight. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;First-that history didn't happen.  Some say that when
I talk about the outpouring of charities in the past, I'm romanticizing.
That's easy to refute: It did happen. Read my footnotes.  The
times I describe were not the good old days.  They were bad in
many ways, but people refused to sit back and take it easy.  They
fought,  and they won. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Second, the history happened but it is irrelevant
to our more complex society today.  That could be true-but when
you see what our predecessors did, you naturally ask yourself,
why not today?  I could go point by point through the comparison
of then and now and show the parallels.  But I'll just say here:
Overall, they had problems.  We have problems.  They dealt with
theirs.  We whine about ours. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;A third criticism comes from members of the religious
left: They say the Bible requires government to transfer to the
poor whatever resources it can grab hold of because Jesus said
that &quot;Whatever you did to the least of these my brethren,
you did it to me.&quot;  I take that verse very seriously.  But
before we blindly use it to justify the welfare state, we need
to ask, who are the least of these in America?  What kind of help
is real help?  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Certainly, children threatened with death before birth
by abortion are among the least of these.   Women abandoned by
their husbands, and children who grow up without fathers, also
have it very rough.   But what about able-bodied homeless men?
Does irresponsibility qualify a person for the ranks of the least
of these?  And how does enabling mothers and fathers to desert
each other help children?  How does the fostering of fatalistic
attitudes help children?
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;A fourth criticism goes like this:  Today,  money
to help the poor won't be forthcoming unless people are taxed
and Washington spends.  But we need to keep two thoughts in mind.
First, much welfare money today is wasted and worse than wasted,
since it actually does harm.   Second, we do need  a system of
tax credits by which taxpayers could send less to the government
and more to private and church charitable organizations that provide
assistance to the poor.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;This is not the place to get into a full-scale discussion
of tax credits, but the idea fits with the distinction I made
earlier between providing and promoting.  We're in our current
mess because the government has attempted to provide welfare rather
than promote civic action.  Tax credits such as those proposed
by  Senator Dan Coats (R-Indiana) and others would promote community-based
poverty-fighting charities by allowing taxpayers to send money
directly to those organizations and take the money off their taxes.

<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;For each dollar taxpayers chose to allocate in this
way, their tax burden would be reduced by that amount-$500 or
$1000 in some plans, more in others.  The  amount of money allocated
to government welfare programs would also decrease, dollar for
dollar, as the private, taxpayer-chosen programs grew.  Tax credits
are a great mechanism for taking money off the top, from the governmental
superstructure, and sticking it back on the bottom, in private
and religious charities, where it can do the most good. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Still, I don't want to fall into the trap of thinking
that a particular piece of legislation is the solution. Tax credits
will work, but they are still just a mechanism, and they will
rust like other mechanisms unless hearts keep them lubricated.
 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;That brings me to the fifth criticism of my testimony
to you: Some pundits say that most Americans just won't help others
anymore.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;And yet, people, ordinary people, are helping others
all over the country: Why can't more? I cannot prove that they
will. As long as government welfare remains, it leads potential
helpers to sit back, since they are paying for someone else to
do it.  We face a Catch-22: We won't have the alternatives until
we need them, but we won't get them as long as government programs
remain in place.  How do we break out of the trap?<BR>

<P>
<H3>Dreams Remembered</H3>

&nbsp;&nbsp;Some people say that there's a public policy answer
here-and tax credits are a partial answer.  But the more time
I spend in Washington, the more I'm reminded of  the recommendation
from a junior high school science class: &quot;For a nosebleed,
put the nose much lower than the body until the heart stops.&quot;

<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;The only way to break through now is to go above and
beyond the call of economic logic-to remember dreams, and to be
moved by God to volunteer to bring them to life.  We need to knock
out the welfare establishment, but we will only be able to do
that if people around the country are able to demonstrate that
the alternatives do work.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;We need to take large leaps, but change starts with
a single step-a single step that each person in this room, whether
you're a college student or whether you've been out in the community
for decades, can take, starting now. Taking that first step will
require an act of will and courage and faith on the part of each
individual.  For many of you with good but hectic jobs, it is
easier to send a check than to suffer with others-but it's that
personal involvement which is desperately needed. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;I'm not very comfortable talking about myself, but
my colleagues have told me that I need to tell people that I've
taken some steps before I ask them to take one themselves. &nbsp;&nbsp;I'll
quickly mention a few of the learning opportunities that God has
put in front of me. At various times my wife and I have been able
to give a room in our home to needy individuals, including a homeless
woman and a pregnant teenager. We've been able to tutor and to
coach kids in baseball, and to mentor many younger men and women.
We've been blessed with three children born to us, and we've been
able to adopt a fourth.  I recommend both methods of family expansion.
We should be doing more.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Here's a confession: I'm not a particularly hospitable
individual.  I'd rather spend time in libraries than on the streets.
And as I've been traveling so much this past year, I've fallen
into the trap that I tell others to avoid:  Maybe helping in little
ways here and there, but not following through consistently enough
with one poor individual. 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;But my failings lead me to think that if once in a
while, I can do something that's a little decent, why can't people
of much finer qualities do the same, or even more? I know very
well, from personal experience,  that many things, including some
good intentions, get in the way of personal involvement with others.
But I'll ask each of you the same question I ask myself:  Can't
we do something?  And why can't we do more? 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;If you try to picture in your mind's eye one poor
person whom you have directly helped during the past year, do
you see anyone? If you do, good-and can you do more?  If you can't
picture anyone, here's the hard question: Will you take a first
step? Will you tutor a child for one hour a week? Will you be
a big brother, a big sister, or a little league coach? Will you
volunteer at an organization in this metropolitan area that offers
true compassion-challenging, personal, and spiritual? Will you
provide biblical counsel to a young, unmarried pregnant woman?
If you are able to do this, will you give her a room in your
home? If you're able to, will you adopt a child? 
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;Sometimes the first step is hard.  But we are surrounded
by hundreds of thousands of people now, and millions over the
past two centuries, who have taken first steps, and many more.
Like you, I have moments of pessimism, but overall I am optimistic:
I am seeing a growing understanding around this country of what
effective compassion is.  First comes thought, then action: I
am hopeful that we will soon see an enormous outpouring of effective
voluntarism. It's as if we have been in a desert, and suddenly
the Red Sea is parted before us and we're beginning to walk through.
I've often wondered how astounded the Israelites must have been
as they walked through.  They must have been amazed-but there
were probably a few who kept muttering, &quot;It's all an optical
illusion.&quot; We're beginning to cross the Red Sea now.  
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;I spent time last year in south central Los Angeles
and on the upper east side of Manhattan.  I talked with people
over lunches in dingy cafeterias and at a few fancy dinners. 
I can say, based on that experience,  that across America people
of many faiths, income levels, and races, are refusing to give
up on the dream of effective compassion. More people are capturing
the understanding  that the major flaw of the modern welfare state
is not that it is extravagant, but that it is too stingy.  It
gives the needy bread and tells them to be content with that alone.
More people are recapturing the optimism that a look at history
can provide.
<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;More people are saying, in the words of the Bible
that are inscribed on the famous bell in Philadelphia, &quot;Proclaim
liberty throughout  the land, and to all the inhabitants thereof.&quot;
Let's not settle for the new slavery of welfare.  Let's be agents
of change who proclaim liberty to all the inhabitants this nation.
With God's grace and your help, we can.<BR>

<P>
Marvin Olasky, founding editor of this publication
and a senior fellow at the Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation in
Washington, delivered this speech last month at Southern Methodist
University.
</BODY>

