<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman">Foundation Watch<p>
</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman">March 1996</font>
<P>
<a href="#Stars">How They Took the Stars and Stripes from the American Center in Paris:<BR>
The Bohen and Mellon Foundations and the Death of a Cultural Institution</A>
<br><a href="#Yanks">The Yanks Are Coming: </a>
<br><a href="#Paris">An American In Paris</a>
<br><a href="#Singing">Singing In The Rain</a>
<br><a href="#Deux">Folie Deux</a>
<br><a href="#Fou">L' amour Fou</a>
<br><a href="#Vanities">Bonfire Of TheVanities</a>
<br><a href="#Deconstructing">Deconstructing The American Center</a>
<br><a href="#Boardroom">Inside The Boardroom></a>
<br><a href="#Who Is">Who Is William Bowen box</a>
<br><a href="#Never">Never Ask Box</a>
<P>
<HR>
<a name="Stars"></a>
<h2></FONT><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman">How They Took the Stars and Stripes from the 
American Center in Paris: </FONT><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman">The Boh<B>e</B>n and 
Mellon Foundations and the Death of a Cultural Institution.</h2>

	On February 12th, 1996, the doors at the American Center at 51, rue de Bercy in the 12th arrondissement 
of Paris closed for the last time.  Eleven days had passed since the death of Gene Kelly, whose MGM film
 <I>An American in Paris</I> had inspired architect Frank Gehry in his design of the Center's new headquarters.
  A white limestone monument designed to resemble a dancer amid the rooftops of the French capital, the
 198,000 square foot structure was less than two years old.  Now it was closing.  The headline in<I> Le
 Monde</I> observed simply:  &quot;A  VENDRE&quot;  (for sale).  The American cultural institution, founded
 in 1931, was &quot;Trop grand, trop cher, trop tard&quot; (too big, too expensive, too late).<p>

	The American Center had suspended most of its operations in 1987, when the original building at 261
 Boulevard Raspail was sold for some $42 million dollars. Gehry's new structure had opened only in June 1994.
  It contained a 400-seat theatre, a 100-seat screening room, a dance studio, art galleries, classrooms and twenty-six 
apartments intended for visiting artists and intellectuals.  At a cost of between $27 and $42 million
 (the figure is disputed), the instant landmark figured to transform an otherwise drab neighborhood of wine
 warehouses east of the city center.<p>  	

	What had happened?  There was a grain of truth to the <I>Le Monde</I> description.  Parisians,
 with the naivete of the sophisticated, expected such follies of Americans.  But to insiders who were familiar
 with the American Center and its history, the closure reveals something more.  The story of how officials from
 two American philanthropic foundations appeared as &quot;White Knights&quot; to rescue a struggling
 cultural institution but stayed to liquidate its assets testifies to the perils of permitting funders to exert direct
 control over organizations.  It also reveals the arrogance of America's avant-garde arts establishment 
during a period of post-Cold War re-evaluation of the U.S. role in Europe.  Finally, it exposes the greed of
 foundation officials who put their private agendas ahead of a nonprofit organization's welfare.
  Ironically, the Bohen and Mellon foundation executives came to Paris not to praise the American Center,
 but to bury it.<P>  

 	***<br>
<hr>
<a name="Yanks"></a>
<H3>THE YANKS ARE COMING</H3>
	The closure and sale of the American Center brought to a distressing end a seven-year run of dreams gone
 awry.  In February, 1987 the original American Center headquarters closed.  Situated in Montparnasse, the Left
 Bank neighborhood which Hemingway and Fitzgerald had made their haunt, it had been a focal point for French
 and American artists and students still searching for the ghosts of the &quot;Lost Generation.&quot;  The Center
 site had been Chateaubriand's garden, and it still sheltered the oldest tree in Paris.<p>

	&quot;The American Students and Artists Center&quot; was founded in 1931 by Frederick Warren Beekman,
 the Dean of the American (Episcopal) Cathedral in Paris (and father-in-law of Presidential candidate Malcolm S. (Steve)
 Forbes, Jr., whose wife Sabina was raised in Paris). The Beekman family owned New York's Social Register (later sold
 to Malcolm S. Forbes) and catered to a striving social elite of expatriate Americans.  Beekman modelled his Center on
 the YMCA, for he intended it to offer an alcohol-free environment protecting Prohibition-era Americans from the
 temptation of cafes while encouraging them to &quot;come to France to partake of its unparalleled culture.&quot;<p> 

	He was immediately successful.  Americans in France formed a 150-member fundraising committee which
 raised $175,000 in Paris and an additional $200,000 in the United States.  Architect Welles Bosworth, brought to
 France by the Rockefeller family to help remodel Versailles, was commissioned to contruct the Center's headquarters,
 a  neo-classical palazzo which contained a swimming pool, gym, bowling alley, billiard room, auditorium, library,
 canteen, enclosed garden, and art studios.  The building was completed in 1934.<p>
<hr>
<a name="Paris"></a>
<H3>AN AMERICAN IN PARIS</H3>
	In the thirties and early forties, the Center was eminently respectable.  The American expatriate community
 enjoyed its events, and it was well-known for its teas, served to patrons in club chairs.  The expatriate American 
community which built the Center was also known for its other good works. It was instrumental in establishing
 an American Hospital, an American Church, and an American Library -- all independent and privately funded -- 
&quot;just as they would be in Minneapolis or Kansas City,&quot; in the words of Henry Pillsbury, heir to the
 Minnesota flour fortune and former executive director of the Center.<p>
	
	During World War II the building was commandeered by the Nazis.  But at war's end Beekman regained the
 building from the French Army and, after retiring as Dean of the Cathedral, became the Center's first executive
 director.  Once independent of the Cathedral, the Center became a venue for American artists in the 1950's and
 60s, sponsoring concerts, theatrical peformances, and exhibitions. In post-war Europe nonconformity became the
 Center's watchword as &quot;beatniks&quot; and avant-garde artists began to change what journalist Claire
 Downey, a reporter for <I>Paris City</I>, called its &quot;Ivy-League, clubby atmosphere.&quot;<p>  

	The Center became known for its bohemian charm and chance <I>rendevous</I> of French and American
 students.  An English language program was instituted, and poetry readings, art and music classes were offered.
  Open all night -- until 7 a.m. -- the Center attracted jazz musicians who would stop by after the French clubs shut
 their doors.  In time, eighty percent of the Center's expenses were paid for by tuition for classes and ticket sales.
 Some 5,000 art students and 3,000 English students enrolled in Center programs annually.  Downey refers to it as
 &quot;a commercial enterprise which supported an artistic agenda.&quot;  This was in keeping with American
 traditions of art and commerce.<p>

	But the Center was changing.  After the rebellious days of the 1968 student uprising, hippies, drugs, and
 theft came to the American Center -- as they did to America itself.  &quot;It was like a small Berkeley,
&quot; observed one-time student Jimmy Shuman.  In 1969 Pillsbury took over as executive director.  In what
 Shuman called &quot;a revolution from the inside,&quot; Pillsbury adopted a new, laid-back approach to
 managing the Center. &quot;He was like a camp counselor,&quot; said one longtime American Paris resident.<p>

	Pillsbury's expatriate American bohemianism was in many ways quite traditional and fundamentally non-political.
  Among some Parisian leftists there were rumors that the Center was involved with the CIA.  In fact, the Minneapolis
 native was simply an eclectic individualist devoted to the arts.  He had once been a theatre director and occasionally 
staged his own productions at the Center. <p> 

	Like his Center, Pillsbury was well-liked by many quite conservative Americans in Paris.  Jean Gerard, President
 Reagan's appointee as U.S. ambassador to UNESCO called him a &quot;fine fellow.&quot;  A &quot;gentleman
&quot; is how he is described by Judith Bingham, a prominent figure among Republicans residing abroad. 
 Pillsbury's devotion to the Center was also quite tangible.  He donated at least $1 million from his personal fortune
 to the Center, making up an annual budget deficit not covered by other revenues.<p>

	The governing board of the Center, made up of primarily expatriate Americans from the listings of Beekman's
 Social Register, had confidence in Pillsbury, who had a relatively free hand as executive director.  &quot;The old
 American Center was deeply loved by both Americans living in Paris and the French,&quot; noted Downey. &quot;It
 was a miracle,&quot; said Michel Reilhac, who later came to work for the Center as its highest-ranking French 
employee, &quot;living on a shoestring it had managed to be a major focus of cultural life in Paris without any means,
 compared to richer French insitutions, which had less cultural influence.&quot;<p>

	In 1977, Pillsbury was joined by Judith Pisar, who had moved to Paris with her husband, Auschwitz survivor
 Samuel Pisar, an international lawyer specializing in East-West trade who represented British publisher Robert Maxwell,
 among others.  A New York City fundraiser for the Brooklyn Academy of Music, Pisar soon became chairman of the
 Center's board after garnering increased contributions.<p>

	Pisar's personal connections helped the Center's fundraising and raised its public profile among the French 
and back home in the United States. Together, Pisar and Pillsbury set their sights on expanding the American Center
 as, in Pillsbury's words, &quot;a place where you can see, where you can learn, and where you can do.&quot;<p> 

	In 1979 Pillsbury and Pisar had secured Rockefeller Foundation funding which supported an &quot;artists
-in-residence&quot; program.  Over the next eight years it would sponsor 500 artistic performances, 350 workshops 
and 30 exhibitions.  Merce Cunningham, John Cage, and Philip Glass graced the Center's stage.  Sources in Paris
 say Pisar was quite close to Republican Senator Charles Percy, who, as Chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
 Committee, worked to better relations between the Center and the USIA and, as father-in-law to Senator John D.
 Rockefeller IV, helped with Center fundraising.<p> 
	
As the decade came to a close, the Center was still a proud and representative American institution in Paris,
 supported by the American establishment and the Franco-American public.<p>	

<hr>
<a name="Singing"></a>
<H3>SINGING IN THE RAIN</H3>
	In 1987, at the height of the Paris real estate boom, Pisar and Pillsbury accepted a fantastic bid of $42 million
 from the Banque Arabe d' Invetissement for the Center's property in Montparnasse.  At that time, the Center's annual
 budget averaged only about $500,000.  The National Endowment for the Arts had given $250,000 to the Center in 1985
 for its endowment fund.  But the enormous pool of new money, Pillsbury and Pisar said, meant that the Center could 
meet ever-rising public demands.  With help from the City of Paris, the Center acquired a huge plot of land in Bercy,
 just across the Seine from the new French library and near the &quot;Palais Omnisport,&quot; a sort of French
 Madison Square Garden.  With $42 million sitting in the Banque National de Paris, Pisar and Pillsbury took a gamble
 and built a monument.<p>
	
	The Center held spectacular fund-raising events in the late 80's and early 90's at such venues as the Theatre
 de le Rond Pont on the Champs Elysees.  They starred the likes of Gene Kelly and Leonard Bernstein, and celebrated
 the elegant fashions of Hubert de Givenchy.  But the eclectic bohemianism of the center was also maintained by
 showcasing avant-garde darlings such as Jean-Louis Barrault and Peter Brook.  During the next decade, Pisar and
 Pillsbury helped raise some $11 million -- in addition to the sale price of the building and accrued interest reaching 
10 percent annually -- including a $5 million dollar matching grant from Minneapolis native and pop art patron  Frederick
 R. Weisman.  Among other old-line donors, the Dillon Foundation and Rockefeller Brothers Fund each gave $100,000.
  Walter Annenberg also made a substantial contribution.  And French companies such as Yves St.Laurent and the 
Banque National de Paris contributed half a million dollars each.  Pisar received a Legion d'Honneur from the French 
government in recognition of her work promoting exchanges of Franco-American culture.<p>

<hr>
<a name="Deux"></a>
<H3>FOLIE A DEUX</H3>
	Unfortunately, the financial windfall for the American Center carried with it some severe problems.  
Freed from the fiscal constraints of the past, Pillsbury and Pisar succumbed to a culture of spending during the
 seven years between buildings.  They executed a series of false starts, made unfortunate staff choices, and relied on
 &quot;consultants&quot; who undermined the Center even as the foundations of its new headquarters were being laid.
<p> 
	
	Michel Reilhac, a French cultural administrator hired by Pillsbury as general manager in 1992, says the Center 
&quot;got trapped in the process of getting rich overnight after having been poor a long time.&quot;  As word spread
 that it had millions in the bank, &quot;a whole group of so-called consultants became attracted to this newly rich
 institution, people who are attracted to making money in this field.&quot;  Reilhac feels that &quot;Pillsbury and
 Pisar didn't know how to say 'No.'&quot;  The result, he argues, was that money began to hemmorhage from the
 Center faster than it could be raised.  It is estimated that some $2 million a year was spent on administration and
 that the projected operating budget for the building was $2 million for programs and $2 million for maintenence.<p>

	To save $5-6 million dollars in construction costs by scaling down the building design, Reilhac flew to
 Los Angeles to meet with the architect, Frank Gehry, whose original design was rejected by zoning officials for the
 City of Paris.  But on returning to Paris, Reilhac discovered that Pisar and Pillsbury had told Gehry to go ahead and
 spend the additional money.<p> 

	Meanwhile, the Center's artistic aspirations were becoming increasingly expensive.  The old American Center
 was a labor of love, but the new operation was paying premiums to its associates.  Pillsbury's friends Martin and
 Mickey Friedman of the Walker Art Center in Minneapolis were among the new &quot;consultants.&quot;  They
 had recommended Gehry as architect and were now assigned to direct the artistic program and decorate the building
 on a retainer estimated by sources at between $10,000 and $20,000 per month.<p>

	To be curator for the Center's art exhibits, Pillsbury then hired Adam Weinberg.  He had worked for Friedman
 at the Walker Art Center before moving to New York City's Whitney Museum.Weinberg reportedly objected to the
 taint of Reilhac's attempts to raise money by renting space to commercial clients from a temporary Center classroom 
building constructed near the Gehry construction site.<p>

	Reilhac also says Weinberg began planning an exceptionally expensive opening exhibition called
 &quot;Landscape as Metaphor,&quot; with Friedman as curator.  Presented with a $1.5 million budget, Reilhac
 asked Weinberg to raise the money.  Friedman got some $500,000 from the Lila Wallace-Reader's Digest Foundation,
 but it was not enough.  In 1992, Pillsbury fired Weinberg, and Friedmansoon left.  Rumored cash settlements 
of $200,000 to Friedman further drained the Center's finances and negative press reactions crimped fundraising.
  &quot;I must say, I have no respect for the Friedmans,&quot; says Reilhac. &quot;They have no idea what
 international culture is about.&quot;<p>

	Soon after the debacle, Pillsbury met Bill Arnett, an Atlanta art collector who manages the career
 of Mississippi's Thornton Dial, an African-American painter and one of the most prominent &quot;Outsider
 Artists&quot; working today.  Pillsbury agreed to an American Center show of Dial's work.  Reilhac describes the
 planned exhibition as &quot;just beautiful work&quot; and Arnett agreed to secure the show's financing at no cost
 to the Center.  Surely the Parisian love affair with African-American culture, from Louis Armstrong and Josephine 
Baker to James Baldwin and Richard Wright, would be rekindled by Dial.<p>

	Whatever their missteps and foolishness, Pillsbury and Pisar had the Center's interests at heart.  It seems
 probable that the American Center could have overcome their <I>folie d'grandeur.</I>  Once the amazing new building
 opened, the Center could have recaptured its role as a vital American presence in France and served as a genuine
 artistic balance to the popular appeal of Euro-Disney. <p>

	The Thornton Dial show was the sort of project that could have led the Center out of the wildneress.  But it
 was not to be. Pillsbury and Pisar lost control of the Center in 1993 after the press stories of its problems reverberated
 through the philanthropic and art communities.  The Center's new leaders cancelled the exhibit of &quot;Outsider
 Art.&quot;  The successors to Pillsbury and Pisar were very much New York art world insiders.<p>
<hr>
<a name="Fou"></a>
<H3>L'AMOUR FOU</H3>
	The final chapter in the collapse of the American Center stars a new cast of characters who assumed center
 stage in 1993:  representatives of the Bohen and Mellon Foundations who took control of the Board of Directors.
  Their role in the destruction of an American cultural institution tells much about the new philanthropy of culture.<p>

	Incredibly, after only eighteen months of operation in its prize-winning building, Frederick Bohen Henry, the
 new Chairman of the American Center's Board of Directors, ordered the Gehry landmark closed and sold.  Henry, the
 president of the Bohen Foundation (assets $6 million), and Rachel Bellow, his partner in the Center's reorganized
 &quot;Office of the Director&quot; and a program officer for the Arts and Humanities at the Andrew G. Mellon 
Foundation (assets $2 billion) preferred to liquidate the American Center's assets.<p>

	This drama took place behind the scenes during 1993 and 1994, as Pillsbury and Pisar were shunted aside
 and a new &quot;special committee&quot; of twenty-five art world superstars shuttled back and forth between 
Paris and the United States prior to the June 1994 opening of the Center.  In Paris, they
 stayed at the fashionable Hotel d'Alembert.  Some reportedly flew first class, others preferred the Concorde. 
 According to sources, neither Henry nor Bellow resided in Paris, preferring to visit for a few days each month.<p>

	While the Center had a New York apartment for &quot;fundraising&quot; purposes, neither of the new leaders
 made a similar commitment to Paris.  This should have been the first sign that neither Henry nor Bellow had the
 interests of the American expatriate community at heart.<p>

	After cancelling the Thornton Dial show, Bellow and Henry cancelled the English classes that Reilhac had
 championed.  They rejected offers from Robert Altman to rent space to produce his film &quot;Pret-A-Porter
&quot; and from Voyager Videodiscs to headquarter its project to digitize the Louvre on CD-ROM.  They even
 turned down a local cafe proprietor who wanted to open a bistro<B>t</B>.  Bettina Zilkha Trink, heiress to a
 Franco-American banking fortune, resigned from the board in disgust.<p>

	Plans for the June, 1994 Center opening continued, and Pillsbury and Pisar agreed to stay on for the sake
 of appearances.  They have never spoken about the final days.  But interviews with their associates make clear 
that by January, 1994, they were mere figureheads and the institution was under the control of the visiting 
Americans.<p>

	Bellow explained her new approach to the <I>Wall Street Journal</I>:  &quot;First we will see how much 
money we can get, and then we'll decide what we are able to do with it.&quot;  One of her first decisions was to 
spend an estimated $500,000 on an opening party.  David Byrne, the former Talking Head, and a gospel group 
provided the music, the decorations were by Andre Puttnam, the liquor flowed, and there was dancing till dawn. <p>

	Among the curious expenses paid by Bellow and Henry was a confidential settlement of a harrassment 
complaint filed by superlawyer Eddie Hayes, current involved in the fight over the Andy Warhol estate and the
 fictionalized protagonist of Tom Wolfe's <I>Bonfire of the Vanities.</I>  Hayes represented an American woman
 hired by the Center to help with fundraising.  How much did her two-month &quot;development&quot; tenure 
cost the Center?  No one is talking, but Hayes did remark, &quot;They were very reasonable.&quot; Coming 
from a plaintiff's lawyer, one can only shudder at the implications.<P>

	Bellow and Henry replaced the no-cost Thornton Dial show with a $250,000 exhibit from Los Angeles'
 Museum of Contemporary Art called &quot;Pure Beauty.&quot;  (Richard Koshalek, the director of L.A. museum,
 was a member of Henry's &quot;special committee&quot;; Bill Arnett was not.)  The show was a flop.  Of &quot;Pure
 Beauty&quot; the <I>Wall Street Journal's</I> Judy Fayard wrote, &quot;Most of it is so hopeless, so lazy, so utterly
 lacking in rigor or vigor or vision, that even the cost of shipping the silly things over seems too much.&quot;<p>


	But the Center's changed tone was noted by the <I>Journal</I> reporter, who quoted Bellow's declaration
 that the Center would now become &quot;a meeting place for an international community of artists and 
performers...&quot; rather than a Franco-American institution.<p>

<hr>
<a name="Vanities"></a>
<H3>BONFIRE OF THE VANITIES</H3>
	In September 1994, the Center hired Marie-Claude Beaud as executive director. She was given a remodeled
 and furnished New York apartment, a travel allowance, and permission to hire her own staff.  Beaud was a French
 cultural bureaucrat, who had managed state-supported museums in Toulon and Grenoble before joining the Fondation
 Cartier, which was, according to <I>Apollo </I>magazine, &quot;better known for its gimmicks and parties than for any
 lasting contribution to modern art.&quot;  Beaud had &quot;never raised a sou&quot; according to one former
 Center employee.  A curious choice for an institution in financial crisis.<p>

	Although Beaud declared in public that she liked America, former Center employees say that in private she 
was &quot;clearly anti-American.&quot;  Soon after her arrival, what had been English and French-language press
 releases were issued only in French.  The policy was not reversed until a prominent American reporter stationed in
 Paris said she would not cover any event without an English-language press release.<p>
	
	Beaud's program decisions parody an NEA annual report:  They include Leon Golub and Nancy Spero's
 left-wing agitprop, &quot;video art&quot; by Nam June Paik and Bill Viola, a Gay and Lesbian Film Festival, and
 presentations by politically correct Nobel laureate Toni Morrison, dancer Bill T. Jones, and Living Theatre relic 
Judith Malina.  Others events included Larry Clark's film on teen sex, &quot;Kids,&quot; art exhibits by European
 artists Phillippe Boardas and Nicholas Bouvier and writers Cees Noteboom and Michel LeBris, and concerts by 
UNUN, with singers &quot;Helda...Thor Eldon, guitarist of the Sugarcubes (Bjork) and Dr. Gunni, an independent
 rock star in Iceland...&quot;  The Center's last cinema event honored the work of Jonas Mekas, whose grainy loops
 of 16mm self-indulgence have a decidedly limited appeal.<p>

	A cynic might conclude that Bellow and Henry must have encouraged such programs to justify their decision
 to sell the building.  Certainly there were alternatives to their selection of <B>Madame Beaud.  </B>Robert Fitzpatrick,
 a Center board member who had headed Euro-Disneyland, the California Institute of the Arts, and the highly 
successful 1984 Los Angeles Olympic Arts Festival expressed interest in the executive director's job.  Pillsbury
 himself had proposed his name.  With contacts in Europe and America and experience in promoting popular and
 high culture, Fitzpatrick could have raised the money and protected the center's mission.  Rebuffed, Fitzpatrick
 became Dean of the Arts at Columbia University.<p>

	Observers close to the scene have revealed to <I>Foundation Watch </I>that Henry and Bellow, who have
 jointly managed the Center's day-to-day affairs since 1994, are personally responsible for sealing its fate.  Depending
 on the sale price of the building, estimates of the potential future endowment range from $10 to $30 million.  Instead 
of raising the money to save what had been an important institution representing American culture to France, the new
 overseers are converting its assets into funds that will be distributed by a grantmaking foundation that will fund art 
from and for &quot;the international community.&quot; <p>

	On January 24, 1996, an American Center press release reported that after the sale of the Gehry landmark
 -- which still awaits a buyer -- and debt repayments including a reported $4 million owed the city of Paris, all remaining
 funds will go into an endowment to be directed by Marie-Claude Beaud, last director of the American Center.  Fred
 Henry will be Chairman of the Board of the newly reorganized fund.  Rachel Bellow announced that she is leaving 
the Mellon Foundation to become a &quot;consultant&quot; to arts organizations.  It was not disclosed whether the
 American Center fund will become her first client. <p>

<hr>
<a name="Deconstructing"></a>
<h3>DECONSTRUCTING THE AMERICAN CENTER</h3>
	The cultural outlook implied in the decisions Henry and Bellow are making derive from the modern-day
 detractors of all things genuinely cultural who currently dominate so much of the art world: the post-modernists
 and deconstructionists who substitute nihilism for aesthetic achievement.  They have little in common with the 
celebration of the buoyant and eclectic American culture usually championed by Pillsbury and Pisar.  Moreover,
 by choosing to redeploy the American Center's financial assets rather than supervise its mission to represent
 American culture, Henry and Bellow are redefining the purposes of philanthrophy. <p>

	How did they manage to takeover the American Center?  In retrospect, there were warnings that should
 not have gone unheeded.  Pillsbury's downfall commenced with his decision to hire Adam Weinberg, late of the
 Walker and Whitney Museums.  It was Weinberg who introduced him to Frederick Bohen Henry.  Henry, a New
 York City attorney and avid art collector, was born in Des Moines, the heir to the Meredith Publishing fortune.
  He remains on the board of the family business, currently valued at some $700 million.  Henry lists his occupation
 as Bohen Foundation president.  (The Bohen board also includes pollster Daniel Yankelovich, co-founder of the
 Public Agenda Foundation.   Bohen gave $125,000 to the Public Agenda Foundation in 1991-92.  See <I>Foundation
 Watch v.I, n.1</I> for more on Public Agenda.)  Most importantly, Henry was a member of the Board of Trustees of 
tNew York's Whitney Museum of American Art.  <p>

	Since the mid-1980s the Walker and Whitney museums have been models and mirrors of the decadence and
 fiscal irresponsibility pervading the American arts establishment.  Representatives of both institutions are
 on Henry's influential &quot;special committee.&quot;  These &quot;cutting edge&quot; venues for self-mutilation
 performances and exhibits of plastic puddles of excrement and vomit have been funded targets of the 
public's outcry against National Endowment for the Arts grants<B>.</B>  (The Walker Museum sponsored the 
HIV-positive artist Ron Athey, who hoisted towels smeared with his victim's blood over the 
heads of art patrons.  The Whitney Biennial featured the poop and puke).  In any future history of the NEA's demise,
 the Walker and the Whitney surely will be featured for their roles in destroying a once bipartisan congressional 
consensus in support of the arts. <p>

	Fred Henry was no stranger to the gross and disgusting.  His Bohen Foundation had been a sponsor of a
 Bruce Nauman exhibit that was shown at the Museum of Modern Art in New York and at the Smithsonian's Hirshorn
 Museum.  It featured neon signs blinking &quot;F--- and Die,&quot; &quot;S--- and Die,&quot; and depicted excited
 male sexual organs and a merry-go-round of slaughtered animals.<p>

	Henry began his courtship of the American Center with a Bohen Foundation donation to support &quot;public
 art&quot; for the park at Bercy.  Well connected in the art-world, he also helped the Center secure money from New 
York City's public art fund in 1989.  By 1990 Bohen was on the American Center's board of directors.  Pisar had stayed
 on as titular Chairman of the board, but Henry in 1992 became Chairman of its Executive Committee.  In that capacity 
he organized the &quot;special committee&quot; of top officials in prominent arts institutions who reported directly 
to him.<P>

	How was Henry able to oust Pillsbury and outmaneuver Pisar? The answer is simple.  He used the assets of
 the Bohen Foundation to increase his influence among the artistic avant-garde so that they would second his 
recommendations on the fate of the American Center. In confronting the troubled institution, Henry's
 aggressive tactics were not unlike those of a corporate takeover artist.  The American Center was a target.  It would
 be a fine institution to run -- or sell -- after a leveraged buyout.  To secure its assets, which were worth over $40 
million, Henry needed only to make investments (i.e. contributions) of mere hundreds of thousands of dollars to 
his allies and then push the old guard aside.<p>

	According to IRS records, in 1991-92 the Bohen Foundation reported a contribution of only $50,000 to the
 American Center in Paris. (Bohen would eventually give about $500,000, roughly half of Henry Pillsbury's personal
 contributions over the years).  More interesting were the Bohen Foundation's grants to other American cultural 
institutions:  $173,000 went to the Whitney Museum of American Art, whose curator of Film and Video, John 
Hanhardt joined the &quot;special committee&quot; of the American Center in 1992; $50,000 went to Social 
Policy Inc. -- The New Press, headed by editor Andre Schiffrin who also joined Henry's &quot;special committee
&quot; in 1992; and $110,000 was contributed to the Museum of Modern Art, whose director, Richard Oldenburg
, joined the &quot;special committee&quot; as well.  A grant of $15,000 went to the Dia Center for the Arts, a venue
 for the avant-garde where Henry was a board member.  Its director joined the &quot;special committee&quot; in 1992,
 as did Harvey Lichtenstein, director of the Brooklyn Academy of Music.  BAM received $57,000 from the Bohen 
Foundation.  Clearly, the members of Henry's &quot;special committee&quot; were aware of his contributions to
 their institutions and unlikely to resist his plans for the Center.<p> 

	In 1994, members of the special committee were invited to join Henry in what an American Center press
 release called &quot;a radical innovation in the management of nonprofit cultural institutions.&quot;  The special
 committee had been &quot;assembled to help formulate and implement the Center's diverse artistic and educational
 program&quot; in order to develop &quot;a new strategic alliance&quot; which &quot;may signal the development 
of a new model for securing international hubs of artistic activity and exchange.&quot;  By such cloudy jargon did the
 arts elite ratify Henry's intention to sell the American Center's new building.  And what justified the sale would be a
 major philanthropy's predatory concept of how nonprofit arts organizations should deploy their resouces.<p> 

<hr>
<a name="Boardroom"></a>
<h3>INSIDE THE BOARDROOM</h3>
		Where did Henry get his ideas about how to proceed in philanthropy?  Some clue may be found in
 <I>Inside the Boardroom</I> (John Wiley, NY, 1994), a new book by William G. Bowen, president of the Andrew 
A. Mellon Foundation.  In his book, Bowen argues that the boards of directors of nonprofit organizations should 
take a more direct role in the day-to-day management of their institutions.  Henry followed this advice when he 
placed himself in power.  But he also innovated.  By consolidating decision-making in an &quot;Office of the Director,
&quot; but then sharing that post with the Mellon Foundation's Rachel Bellow, Henry devised a novel experiment in 
organizational infrastructure.<p>

	Henry's reliance on his &quot;special committee&quot; perhaps reflects Bowen's endorsement of outside
 consultants as a highly desirable board practice.  Bowen, a former president of Princeton University who once
 managed the private trusts of the Rockefeller family (estimated by <I>Fortune</I> magazine in 1986 to be worth some
 $3 billion) argues that good management requires &quot;the board should have ready access to advice from
 accountants, compensation consultants, lawyers, and investment bankers who are chosen by the outside directors,
 not by management,&quot; (i.e. the American Center's case, not Pillsbury and Pisar).   <p>

		More importantly, in <I>Inside the Boardroom, </I>Bowen specifically credits Rachel Bellow, Mellon's
 program officer on the American Center board, for helping reconcile the Center to its own suicide.  Concludes Bowen:
  &quot;More thought needs to be given, in my view, to ways of allowing nonprofits to achieve 'death with dignity'
 when that is appropriate.  In theory, some nonprofits recognize that institutional demise can signal success, not failure.
 . .For example, my colleague, Rachel Bellow, has called my attention to the Free Southern Theatre in New Orleans. . .The
 theater staged a large funeral through the streets of New Orleans and artists from all over the country attended to 
celebrate the 'death' (read:success) of the theater.&quot;<p>  

	What occurred in New Orleans foreshadowed what followed in Paris.  By hiring Marie-Claude Beaud
 as Pillsbury's successor, Henry and Bellow selected more than a promoter of the international avant-garde. 
 The former curator at the Fondation Cartier dreamed about shutting down cultural institutions
</B>Beaud once actually once told a journalist that she would like to close Cartier's museum and sell its collection. 
 In September 1992 she declared to Elspeth Moncrieff of Britain's <I>Apollo</I> magazine: &quot;With the ease of
 modern-day travel it makes more sense for the Fondation to contribute to existing centres of excellence, rather than
 create another institution in a minor Parisian suburb...There is no point in continuing to build our own collection...
If you have a collection, you need a museum and curators.  Even lending the works involves a good deal of
 administration all of which eats into our grant.  If I had my way I would give away the Fondation's collection,
 with the exception of the works which hang in our corporate offices.&quot;  When she took over the American
 Center one could ask for no clearer statement of Beaud's philosophy.<p>

		In his new mission statement for the Center, Henry declared his constituency to be not Americans
 or the French, but &quot;an international community.&quot;  He promised &quot;an entrepreneurship of new 
expressions.&quot;  Henry had made sure that he was joined in his venture by the most powerful officials from 
America's private arts bureaucracy.  And to the modest assets of his Bohen Foundation he added the backing of
 William Bowen's Andrew Mellon Foundation, whose $2 billion in assets makes it the largest single grantmaker in
 the arts and humanities in the United States. <p>

		Rachel Bellow, the woman who advised Bowen on the successful death of the New Orleans theater,
 is a program officer in the arts and humanities at the Mellon Foundation.  Her division alone distributes some $20 
million annually.  Bellow is widely considered an expert on arts management.  She has served as a consultant to the
 NEA and is married to Adam Bellow, an important neoconservative editor at The Free Press who is the son of novelist
 Saul Bellow.  Like the other art world denizens selected by Fred Henry, Bellow had been invited to join his
 &quot;special committee&quot; in 1992 for a purpose.  She was given leave by the Mellon Foundation for her
 new assignment. By 1993 Bellow was Henry's full partner in the newly constituted &quot;Office of the Director.
&quot;  But what was her purpose?<p>

		Some might have supposed that the Mellon Foundation would open its deep pockets to the Center.  
Former Center staffers thought so.  In 1993, Bellow's division in the Mellon Foundation gave $15 million in a single 
grant to the National Gallery of Art.  But they would misjudge the intentions of Henry and Bellow.<p>

		Consider, for instance, the disposition of a $440,000 Mellon grant to the American Center in 1993
 which was personally approved by William Bowen.  Mellon's annual report claims the grant went &quot;to 
strengthen its [the American Center's] core programs, collaborations with smaller arts organizations and financial
 stability.&quot;  Did the report's bland prose admit of a new definition for the Center's &quot;core programs,
&quot; or was the report a misrepresentation to the Mellon Foundation's board?<p>

		Certainly, the Mellon Foundation could have rescued the American Center had Bowen wished it.
  Would Mellon's Board Chairman, John C. Whitehead, Deputy Secretary of State in the Reagan Administration 
and a former head of Goldman, Sachs, have permitted the sinking of a flagship American cultural institution?  
Indeed, Bowen's book quoted Whitehead's own personal observation that &quot;A for-profit board has an 
obligation to <I>get out</I> of a bad business while a nonprofit board may have an obligation to <I>stay in</I>,
 if it is to be true to its mission.&quot;  <p>

		The mystery is that Henry, Bowen and Bellow were indifferent to such basic obligations.  Should
 not Whitehead call them to account for their decision to kill the symbol of American culture in Paris?  After all, it
 was William Bowen himself who wrote in <I>Inside the Boardroom, &quot;Nonprofit boards are tremendously 
important.  They can have more impact on the success or failure of an organization than can most for-profit 
boards.&quot;</I><p>





***
<hr>
<a name="Who Is"></a>
<h3>WHO IS WILLIAM BOWEN</h3>
	William Bowen is widely perceived as a mentor to University of Pennsylvania President Sheldon Hackney,
 the Clinton Administration's selection for Chairman of the National Endowment for the Humanities.  A 1965 Bowen
 study laid much of the groundwork for the National Endowment for the Arts.<p>

***
<hr>
<a name="Never"></a>
<h3>	NEVER ASKED BOX</h3>
<b> 		Anne Radice, the first director of the National Museum of Women in the Arts (and acting chairman of
 the National Endowment for the Arts under President Bush) pointed out, she had built a new museum, with a new 
constituency, and an income-generating membership, with programs that required an annual operating budget of 
$6 million. And the National Museum of Women in the Arts did it without any endowment, and in a building which
 required monthly mortgage payments, and an initial $5 million renovation. <p>

		How did she do it? &quot;We were careful how we spent our money,&quot; Radice says. &quot;I
 wouldn't do an exhibit without underwriting. Never. We paid for everything before we did it. I never planned a budget
 on the receipt of grants.  And so we never had to fire people. Every night when I went to bed, I felt personally 
responsible for all of our employees. I would never have jeopardized their jobs.&quot;Clearly, had the American
 Center asked Radice, who has a MBA in addition to her doctorate in Art History (in Florentine art), and experience
 as an international cultural officer with USIA specializing in public diplomacy, she might have been able to help them
 out. The sad part is, as she notes, &quot;I was never approached.&quot;Ironically, Radice became available in
 November, 1992, when President Bush lost his bid for-re-election. Today she is involved with a different private
 foundation, not funding the arts.<p>

</B>(Architect Gehry disputes the figure, assigning a cost of $27 million, including architect's fees). 

 (Sadly, this relic was chopped down by the Fondation Cartier, the corporate foundation of the jewelry business, 
when it took over the site in 1990.) 
